# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: banana
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:banana/abaca] The lustrous fiber is traditionally hand-loomed into various indigenous textiles (**abaca cloth** or **medriñaque**) in the Philippines.
[src:banana/abaca] They are still featured prominently as the traditional material of the barong tagalog, the national male attire of the Philippines, as well as in sheer lace-like fabrics called *nipis* used in various clothing components.
[src:banana/abaca] Native abaca textiles also survive into the modern era among various ethnic groups, like the *t'nalak* of the T'boli people and the *dagmay* of the Bagobo people.
[src:banana/abaca] Abaca is also used in traditional Philippine millinery, as well as for bags, shawls, and other decorative items.
[src:banana/abaca] The hatmaking straw made from Manila hemp is called *tagal* or *tagal straw*.
[src:banana/abaca] The fiber is also exceptionally strong, stronger than hemp and naturally salt-resistant, making it ideal for making twines and ropes (especially for maritime shipping).
[src:banana/abaca] It became a major trade commodity in the colonial era for this reason.
[src:banana/abaca] The abaca industry declined sharply in the mid-20th century when abaca plantations were decimated by World War II and plant diseases, as well as the invention of nylon in the 1930s.
[src:banana/abaca] Today, abaca is mostly used in a variety of specialized paper products including tea bags, filter paper and banknotes.
[src:banana/abaca] Manila envelopes and Manila paper derive their name from this fiber.
[src:banana/abaca] Abaca is classified as a hard fiber, along with coir, henequin and sisal.
[src:banana/abaca] Abaca is grown as a commercial crop in the Philippines, Ecuador, and Costa Rica.
[src:banana/abaca] The abacá plant is stoloniferous, meaning that the plant produces runners or shoots along the ground that then root at each segment.
[src:banana/abaca] Cutting and transplanting rooted runners is the primary technique for creating new plants, since seed growth is substantially slower.
[src:banana/abaca] Abacá has a "false trunk" or pseudostem about 6–15 inches (15–38 cm) in diameter.
[src:banana/abaca] The leaf stalks (petioles) are expanded at the base to form sheaths that are tightly wrapped together to form the pseudostem.
[src:banana/abaca] There are from 12 to 25 leaves, dark green on the top and pale green on the underside, sometimes with large brown patches.
[src:banana/abaca] They are oblong in shape with a deltoid base.
[src:banana/abaca] The petioles grow to at least 1 foot (30 cm) in length.
[src:banana/abaca] When the plant is mature, the flower stalk grows up inside the pseudostem.
[src:banana/abaca] The male flower has five petals, each about 1.5 inches (3.8 cm) long.
[src:banana/abaca] The leaf sheaths contain the valuable fiber.
[src:banana/abaca] After harvesting, the coarse fibers range in length from 6–12 feet (180–370 cm) long.
[src:banana/abaca] They are composed primarily of cellulose, lignin, and pectin.
[src:banana/abaca] The fruit, which is inedible and is rarely seen as harvesting occurs before the plant fruits, grows to about 2–3 inches (5.1–7.6 cm) in length and 1 inch (2.5 cm) in diameter.
[src:banana/abaca] It has black turbinate seeds that are 0.167 inches (0.42 cm) in diameter.
[src:banana/abaca] The abacá plant belongs to the banana family, Musaceae; it resembles the closely related wild seeded bananas, *Musa acuminata* and *Musa balbisiana*.
[src:banana/abaca] Within the genus *Musa*, it is placed in section *Callimusa* (now including the former section *Australimusa*), members of which have a diploid chromosome number of 2n= 20.
[src:banana/abaca] The Philippines, especially the Bicol region in Luzon, has the most abaca genotypes and cultivars.
[src:banana/abaca] Genetic analysis using simple sequence repeats (SSR) markers revealed that the Philippines' abaca germplasm is genetically diverse.
[src:banana/abaca] Abaca genotypes in Luzon had higher genetic diversity than Visayas and Mindanao.
[src:banana/abaca] Ninety-five (95) percent was attributed to molecular variance within the population, and only 5% of the molecular variance to variation among populations.
[src:banana/abaca] Genetic analysis by Unweighted Pair Group Method with Arithmetic Mean (UPGMA) revealed several clusters irrespective of geographical origin.
[src:banana/abaca] Before synthetic textiles came into use, *M. textilis* was a major source of high quality fiber: soft, silky and fine.
[src:banana/abaca] Ancestors of the modern abacá are thought to have originated from the eastern Philippines, where there is significant rainfall throughout the year.
[src:banana/abaca] Wild varieties of abacá can still be found in the interior forests of the island province of Catanduanes, away from cultivated areas.
[src:banana/abaca] Today, Catanduanes has many other modern kinds of abacá which are more competitive.
[src:banana/abaca] For many years, breeders from various research institutions have made the cultivated varieties of Catanduanes even more competitive in local and international markets.
[src:banana/abaca] This results in the optimum production of the island which had a consistent highest production throughout the archipelago.
[src:banana/abaca] Europeans first came into contact with Abacá fibre when Ferdinand Magellan landed in the Philippines in 1521, as the natives were already cultivating it and utilizing it in bulk for textiles.
[src:banana/abaca] Throughout the Spanish colonial era, it was referred to as "*medriñaque*" cloth.
[src:banana/abaca] By 1897, the Philippines were exporting almost 100,000 tons of abacá, and it was one of the three biggest cash crops, along with tobacco and sugar.
[src:banana/abaca] In fact, from 1850 through the end of the 19th century, sugar or abacá alternated with each other as the biggest export crop of the Philippines.
[src:banana/abaca] This 19th-century trade was predominantly with the United States and the making of ropes was done mainly in New England, although in time rope-making shifted back to the Philippines.
[src:banana/abaca] From 1898 to 1946, the United States colonized the Philippines following the Spanish–American War.
[src:banana/abaca] In the early 1900s, a train running from Danao to Argao would transport Philippine abacá from the plantations to Cebu City for export.
[src:banana/abaca] The railway system was destroyed during World War II; the abaca continues to be transported to Cebu by road.
[src:banana/abaca] Outside the Philippines, abacá was first cultivated on a large scale in Sumatra in 1925 under the Dutch, who had observed its cultivation in the Philippines for cordage since the nineteenth century, followed up by plantings in Central America in 1929 sponsored by the U.S.
[src:banana/abaca] It also was transplanted into India and Guam.
[src:banana/abaca] Commercial planting began in 1930 in British North Borneo; at the onset of World War II, the supply from the Philippines was eliminated by the Empire of Japan.
[src:banana/abaca] Department of Agriculture started production in Panama, Costa Rica, Honduras, and Guatemala.
[src:banana/abaca] Today, abacá is produced primarily in the Philippines and Ecuador.
[src:banana/abaca] The Philippines produces between 85% and 95% of the world's abacá, and the production employs 1.5 million people.
[src:banana/abaca] Production has declined because of virus diseases.
[src:banana/abaca] The plant is normally grown in well-drained loamy soil, using rhizomes planted at the start of the rainy season.
[src:banana/abaca] In addition, new plants can be started by seeds.
[src:banana/abaca] Growers harvest abacá fields every three to eight months after an initial growth period of 12–25 months.
[src:banana/abaca] Harvesting is done by removing the leaf-stems after flowering but before the fruit appears.
[src:banana/abaca] The plant loses productivity between 15 and 40 years.
[src:banana/abaca] The slopes of volcanoes provide a preferred growing environment.
[src:banana/abaca] When the processing is complete, the bundles of fiber are pale and lustrous with a length of 6–12 feet (1.8–3.7 m).
[src:banana/abaca] In Costa Rica, more modern harvest and drying techniques are being developed to accommodate the very high yields obtained there.
[src:banana/abaca] According to the Philippine Fiber Industry Development Authority, the Philippines provided 87.4% of the world's abacá in 2014, earning the Philippines US$111.33 million.
[src:banana/abaca] The demand is still greater than the supply.
[src:banana/abaca] The remainder came from Ecuador (12.5%) and Costa Rica (0.1%).
[src:banana/abaca] The Bicol region in the Philippines produced 27,885 metric tons of abacá in 2014, the largest of any Philippine region.
[src:banana/abaca] The Philippine Rural Development Program (PRDP) and the Department of Agriculture reported that in 2009–2013, Bicol Region had a 39% share of Philippine abacá production of which an overwhelming 92% came from Catanduanes Island.
[src:banana/abaca] Eastern Visayas, the second largest producer had 24% and the Davao Region, the third largest producer had 11% of the total production.
[src:banana/abaca] Around 42 percent of the total abacá fiber shipments from the Philippines went to the United Kingdom in 2014, making it the top importer.
[src:banana/abaca] Germany imported 37.1 percent abacá pulp from the Philippines, importing around 7,755 metric tons (MT).
[src:banana/abaca] Sales of abacá cordage surged 20 percent in 2014 to a total of 5,093MT from 4,240MT, with the United States holding around 68 percent of the market.
[src:banana/abaca] Abacá is vulnerable to a number of pathogens, notably abaca bunchy top virus, abaca bract mosaic virus, and abaca mosaic virus.
[src:banana/abaca] Due to its strength, it is a sought after product and is the strongest of the natural fibers.
[src:banana/abaca] It is used by the paper industry for such specialty uses such as tea bags, banknotes and decorative papers.
[src:banana/abaca] It can be used to make handcrafts such as hats, bags, carpets, clothing and furniture.
[src:banana/abaca] Abacá fibers were traditionally woven into sturdy textiles and clothing in the Philippines since pre-colonial times.
[src:banana/abaca] Along with cotton, they were the main source of textile fibers used for clothing in the pre-colonial Philippines.
[src:banana/abaca] Abacá cloth was often compared to calico in terms of texture and was a major trade commodity in the pre-colonial maritime trade and the Spanish colonial era.
[src:banana/abaca] There are multiple traditional types and names of abaca cloth among the different ethnic groups of the Philippines.
[src:banana/abaca] Undyed plain abacá cloth, woven from fine fibers of abaca, is generally known as *sinamáy* in most of the islands.
[src:banana/abaca] Abacá cloth with a more delicate texture is called *tinampipi*.
[src:banana/abaca] While especially fine lace-like abacá cloth is called *nipis* or *lupis*.
[src:banana/abaca] Fine abacá fibers may also be woven with *piña*, silk, or fine cotton to create a fabric called *jusi*.
[src:banana/abaca] Traditional abacá textiles were often dyed in various colors from various natural dyes.
[src:banana/abaca] These include blue from indigo (*tarum*, *dagum*, *tayum*, etc.); black from ebony (*knalum* or *batulinao*) leaves; red from noni roots and *sapang*; yellow from turmeric (*kalawag*, *kuning*, etc.); and so on.
[src:banana/abaca] They were often woven into specific patterns, and further ornamented with embroidery, beadwork, and other decorations.
[src:banana/abaca] Most clothing made from abacá took the form of the *baro* (also *barú* or *bayú*, literally "shirt" or "clothing"), a simple collar-less shirt or jacket with close-fitting long sleeves worn by both men and women in most ethnic groups in the pre-colonial Philippines.
[src:banana/abaca] These were paired with wraparound sarong-like skirts (for both men and women), close-fitting pants, or loincloths (*bahag*).
[src:banana/abaca] During the Spanish colonial era, abacá cloth became known as **medriñaque** in Spanish (apparently derived from a native Cebuano name).
[src:banana/abaca] They were exported to other Spanish colonies since the 16th century.
[src:banana/abaca] A waistcoat of a native Quechua man in Peru was recorded as being made of medriñaque as early as 1584.
[src:banana/abaca] Abacá cloth also appear in English records, spelled variously as **medrinacks**, **medrianacks**, **medrianackes**, and **medrinacles**, among other names.
[src:banana/abaca] They were used as canvas for sails and for stiffening clothing like skirts, collars, and doublets.
[src:banana/abaca] Philippine indigenous tribes still weave abacá-based textiles like *t'nalak*, made by the Tiboli tribe of South Cotabato, and *dagmay*, made by the Bagobo people.
[src:banana/abaca] Abacá cloth is found in museum collections around the world, like the Boston Museum of Fine Arts and the Textile Museum of Canada.
[src:banana/abaca] The inner fibers are also used in the making of hats, including the "Manila hats", slippers, hammocks, matting, cordage, ropes, coarse twines, and types of canvas.
[src:banana/abaca] Manila rope is a type of rope made from manila hemp.
[src:banana/abaca] Manila rope is very durable, flexible, and resistant to salt water damage, allowing its use in rope, hawsers, ships' lines, and fishing nets.
[src:banana/abaca] A 1 inch (2.5 cm) rope can require 4 metric tons (8,800 lb) to break.
[src:banana/abaca] Manila rope is still the only material specified for lifeboat falls (the ropes with which a ship's lifeboat is lowered) in the United Kingdom.
[src:banana/abaca] Manila ropes shrink when they become wet.
[src:banana/abaca] This effect can be advantageous under certain circumstances, but if it is not a wanted feature, it should be well taken into account.
[src:banana/abaca] Since shrinkage is more pronounced the first time the rope becomes wet, new rope is usually immersed into water and put to dry before use so that the shrinkage is less than it would be if the rope had never been wet.
[src:banana/abaca] A major disadvantage in this shrinkage is that many knots made with manila rope became harder and more difficult to untie when wet, thus becoming subject of increased stress.
[src:banana/abaca] Manila rope will rot after a period of time when exposed to saltwater.
[src:banana/abaca] Manila hemp rope was previously the favoured variety of rope used for executions by hanging, both in the U.K. and USA.
[src:banana/abaca] Usually 3⁄4 to 1 inch (19 to 25 mm) diameter, boiled prior to use to take out any overelasticity.
[src:banana/abaca] Abacá fiber was once used primarily for rope, but this application is now of minor significance.
[src:banana/abc-clio] ABC-Clio provides service to fifteen different online databases which contain over one million online textbooks.
[src:banana/abc-clio] The company consults academic leaders in the fields they cover in order to provide authority for their reference titles.
[src:banana/abc-clio] The headquarters are located in Santa Barbara, California.
[src:banana/abc-clio] ABC-Clio was founded in 1955 as a privately held corporation by Eric Boehm with its first publication, *Historical Abstracts*.
[src:banana/abc-clio] The name represents the company's two original divisions when it incorporated in 1969: ABC stands for American Bibliographical Center and Clio Press is named after Clio, the muse of history from ancient Greek mythology.
[src:banana/abc-clio] According to Boehm, he had always been interested in history so when he noticed that there were not many good historical abstracting services available, he started publishing the *Historical Abstracts*.
[src:banana/abc-clio] During the 1960s, a sister bibliographic and abstract publication on American history was added, *America: History and Life*, which was considered an award-winning title.
[src:banana/abc-clio] The company entered into digital publishing with electronic data in the 1960s and in 1975, it published its first online database called *DIALOG*.
[src:banana/abc-clio] During the 1980s, ABC-Clio expanded into providing primary reference books such as encyclopedias and dictionaries and stopped publishing bibliographic books.
[src:banana/abc-clio] In the 1990s, ABC-Clio began to provide access to its humanities database on CD-ROM.
[src:banana/abc-clio] The *Exegy Current Events* CD-ROM was named "Best Disc of the Year" by Library Journal.
[src:banana/abc-clio] In 1998, ABC-Clio provided electronic access to *America: History and Life*.
[src:banana/abc-clio] By the 2000s, one of the company's most popular products had become online databases for researching many topics in the field of the humanities.
[src:banana/abc-clio] In 2001, ABC-Clio began to publish eBooks, initially providing 150 different titles to schools and libraries.
[src:banana/abc-clio] The company's reference books had won numerous awards, and the company started a series of subject-related online databases for secondary school use.
[src:banana/abc-clio] In 2004, the company acquired the quarterly historical journal, *Journal of the West*, which has been published since 1962.
[src:banana/abc-clio] In 1996, ABC-Clio merged with an electronic publishing company, Intellimation, which also produced educational software.
[src:banana/abc-clio] The merger brought Becky Snyder, who by 2009 had become ABC-Clio's president, from Intellimation.
[src:banana/abc-clio] In 2007, it sold two databases – *Historical Abstracts* and *America: History and Life* – to EBSCO Publishing; in addition, the companies also agreed a partnership through which nine additional ABC-Clio databases would be distributed through EBSCO Publishing.
[src:banana/abc-clio] In December 2021, Bloomsbury Publishing acquired ABC-Clio for US$22.9 million (equivalent to $26.1 million in 2024).
[src:banana/abc-clio] In 2008, ABC-Clio acquired the Greenwood Publishing Group from Houghton Mifflin Harcourt.
[src:banana/abc-clio] The deal gave ABC-Clio a "perpetual license" to use the imprints of Greenwood Press and publish all of its titles.
[src:banana/abc-clio] Acquiring the publishing group gave ABC-Clio access to Greenwood Press, Praeger Publishers, Praeger Security International, and Libraries Unlimited.
[src:banana/abc-clio] Greenwood focuses on publishing full-text reference works which are authoritative on various topics.
[src:banana/abc-clio] Libraries Unlimited came to ABC-Clio as part of a deal with Greenwood Press.
[src:banana/abc-clio] In 2012, Kathyrn Suárez was named publisher for this division, which focuses on publishing for librarians and information professionals.
[src:banana/abc-clio] ABC-Clio databases are provided under the umbrella of ABC-Clio Solutions.
[src:banana/abc-clio] There are fifteen different databases providing access to different subject areas.
[src:banana/abc-clio] ABC-Clio Solutions provides digital curriculum with multimedia content, text-to-speech features, translation tools which covers various topics relating to history and the humanities.
[src:banana/abc-clio] After ABC-Clio acquired Greenwood Press's databases, they revamped the look and feel of their interface in order to provide common access through the ABC-Clio interface.
[src:banana/abc-clio] ABC-Clio also provided the ability to search across multiple databases through one search, also providing options for narrowing the search after revamping their interface.
[src:banana/abc-clio] The new interface is considered user-friendly and provides access to personalized features.
[src:banana/abc-clio] Originally publishing books by disillusioned former Communists who had fled from behind the Iron Curtain, the publishing house became known for publishing "scholarly and professional books" in the subject areas of social sciences and the humanities.
[src:banana/abc-clio] In 1966, Praeger sold his firm to William B.
[src:banana/abc-clio] Benton, an American senator and publisher and the chairman of *Encyclopaedia Britannica*.
[src:banana/abc-clio] In 1976, it was sold to CBS, which had shortened the name to Praeger Publishing before selling it to Greenwood Press, Inc., in 1986.
[src:banana/abc-clio] When the renamed Greenwood Publishing Group (GPG) was acquired by ABC-Clio in 2009, Praeger Publishing became a standalone imprint of ABC-Clio, and remained such when, in December 2021, Bloomsbury Publishing bought ABC-Clio.
[src:banana/abiotic-component] In ecology, **abiotic components** or **abiotic factors** are non-living chemical and physical parts of the environment that affect living organisms and the functioning of ecosystems.
[src:banana/abiotic-component] Abiotic factors and the phenomena associated with them underpin biology as a whole.
[src:banana/abiotic-component] They affect a wide range of species, across all forms of environmental conditions, such as marine or terrestrial animals.
[src:banana/abiotic-component] Humans can make or change abiotic factors in a species' environment.
[src:banana/abiotic-component] For instance, fertilizers can affect a snail's habitat, or the greenhouse gases which humans utilize can change marine pH levels.
[src:banana/abiotic-component] Abiotic components include physical conditions and non-living resources that affect living organisms in terms of growth, maintenance, and reproduction.
[src:banana/abiotic-component] Resources are distinguished as substances or objects in the environment required by one organism and consumed or otherwise made unavailable for use by other organisms.
[src:banana/abiotic-component] Component degradation of a substance occurs by chemical or physical processes, e.g. hydrolysis.
[src:banana/abiotic-component] All non-living components of an ecosystem, such as atmospheric conditions and water resources, are called abiotic components.
[src:banana/abiotic-component] In biology, abiotic factors can include water, light, radiation, temperature, humidity, atmosphere, acidity, salinity, precipitation, altitude, minerals, tides, rain, dissolved oxygen nutrients, and soil.
[src:banana/abiotic-component] The macroscopic climate often influences each of the above.
[src:banana/abiotic-component] Pressure and sound waves may also be considered in the context of marine or sub-terrestrial environments.
[src:banana/abiotic-component] Abiotic factors in ocean environments also include aerial exposure, substrate, water clarity, solar energy and tides.
[src:banana/abiotic-component] Consider the differences in the mechanics of C3, C4, and CAM plants in regulating the influx of carbon dioxide to the Calvin-Benson Cycle in relation to their abiotic stressors.
[src:banana/abiotic-component] C3 plants have no mechanisms to manage photorespiration, whereas C4 and CAM plants utilize a separate PEP carboxylase enzyme to prevent photorespiration, thus increasing the yield of photosynthesis processes in certain high energy environments.
[src:banana/abiotic-component] Many Archea require very high temperatures, pressures, or unusual concentrations of chemical substances such as sulfur; this is due to their specialization into extreme conditions.
[src:banana/abiotic-component] In addition, fungi have also evolved to survive at the temperature, the humidity, and stability of their environment.
[src:banana/abiotic-component] For example, there is a significant difference in access to both water and humidity between temperate rain forests and deserts.
[src:banana/abiotic-component] This difference in water availability causes a diversity in the organisms that survive in these areas.
[src:banana/abiotic-component] These differences in abiotic components alter the species present by creating boundaries of what species can survive within the environment and influencing competition between two species.
[src:banana/abiotic-component] Abiotic factors such as salinity can give one species a competitive advantage over another, creating pressures that lead to speciation and alteration of a species to and from generalist and specialist competitors.
[src:banana/acta-eruditorum] After Otto Mencke's death in 1707, *Acta Eruditorum* was directed by his son, Johann Burckhardt Mencke, who died in 1732.
[src:banana/acta-eruditorum] The journal had changed its name by then to ***Nova Acta Eruditorum***.
[src:banana/acta-eruditorum] Beginning in 1756 it was led by Karl Andreas Bel.
[src:banana/acta-eruditorum] Although Mencke once exchanged letters and publications with Isaac Newton, Newton was not a correspondent of *Acta*.
[src:banana/acta-eruditorum] In the following acrimonious squabble, *Acta* by and large acted as a mouthpiece for Leibniz's camp, much as *Philosophical Transactions* did for Newton's.
[src:banana/acta-eruditorum] Mencke tried to tone down the dispute, but rebuttals from both sides were too forceful.
[src:banana/acta-eruditorum] "Where Mencke was powerless to call the tune, he did his utmost at least to set the tone," says H.
[src:banana/acta-eruditorum] This dispute also influenced *Acta* to express the feelings of national cohesion and defining German scholarship within the international field of influence.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Africa straddles the equator and the prime meridian.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The continent is surrounded by the Mediterranean Sea to the north, the Arabian plate and the Gulf of Aqaba to the northeast, the Indian Ocean to the southeast and the Atlantic Ocean to the west.
[src:banana/africa-p01] France, Italy, Portugal, Spain, and Yemen have parts of their territories located on African geographical soil, mostly in the form of islands.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The continent includes Madagascar and various archipelagos.
[src:banana/africa-p01] It contains 54 fully recognised sovereign states, eight cities and islands that are part of non-African states, and two *de facto* independent states with limited or no recognition.
[src:banana/africa-p01] This count does not include Malta and Sicily, which are geologically part of the African continent.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Algeria is Africa's largest country by area, and Nigeria is its largest by population.
[src:banana/africa-p01] African nations cooperate through the establishment of the African Union, which is headquartered in Addis Ababa.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Africa is highly biodiverse; it is the continent with the largest number of megafauna species, as it was least affected by the extinction of the Pleistocene megafauna.
[src:banana/africa-p01] However, Africa is also heavily affected by a wide range of environmental issues, including desertification, deforestation, water scarcity, and pollution.
[src:banana/africa-p01] These entrenched environmental concerns are expected to worsen as climate change impacts Africa.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The UN Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change has identified Africa as the continent most vulnerable to climate change.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The history of Africa is long, complex, and varied, and has often been under-appreciated by the global historical community.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In African societies the oral word is revered, and they have generally recorded their history via oral tradition, which has led anthropologists to term them "oral civilisations", contrasted with "literate civilisations" which pride the written word.
[src:banana/africa-p01] African culture is rich and diverse both within and between the continent's regions, encompassing art, cuisine, music and dance, religion, and dress.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Africa, particularly Eastern Africa, is widely accepted to be the place of origin of humans and the Hominidae clade, also known as the great apes.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The earliest hominids and their ancestors have been dated to around 7 million years ago, and *Homo sapiens* (modern human) are believed to have originated in Africa 350,000 to 260,000 years ago.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Throughout history the continent saw the rise and fall of many kingdoms and empires, such as Ancient Egypt, Makuria, the Fatimids, Mali, the Asante, Kongo, the Luba, Bunyoro, Great Zimbabwe, Imerina, and the Zulu.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Despite the predominance of states, many societies were heterarchical and stateless.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Slave trades created various diasporas, especially in the Americas.
[src:banana/africa-p01] From the late-19th century to early 20th century, driven by the Second Industrial Revolution, most of Africa was rapidly conquered and colonised by European nations, save for Ethiopia and Liberia.
[src:banana/africa-p01] European rule had significant impacts on Africa's societies, and colonies were maintained for the purpose of economic exploitation and extraction of natural resources.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Most present states emerged from a process of decolonisation following World War II, and established the Organisation of African Unity in 1963, the predecessor to the African Union.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The nascent countries decided to keep their colonial borders, with traditional power structures used in governance to varying degrees.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Under Roman rule, Carthage became the capital of the province then named *Africa Proconsularis*, following the Roman victory over the Carthaginians in the Third Punic War in 146 BC, which also included the coastal part of modern Libya.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The Latin suffix *-ica* can sometimes be used to denote a land (e.g., in *Celtica* from *Celtae*, as used by Julius Caesar).
[src:banana/africa-p01] The later Muslim region of Ifriqiya, following its conquest of the Byzantine (Eastern Roman) Empire's *Exarchatus Africae*, also preserved a form of the name.
[src:banana/africa-p01] According to the Romans, Africa lies to the west of Egypt, while "Asia" was used to refer to Anatolia and lands to the east.
[src:banana/africa-p01] A definite line was drawn between the two continents by the geographer Ptolemy (85–165 CE), indicating Alexandria along the Prime Meridian and making the isthmus of Suez and the Red Sea the boundary between Asia and Africa.
[src:banana/africa-p01] As Europeans came to understand the real extent of the continent, the idea of "Africa" expanded with their knowledge.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In accordance with African cosmology, African historical consciousness viewed historical change and continuity, order and purpose within the framework of man and his environment, the gods, and his ancestors, and he believed himself part of a holistic spiritual entity.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In African societies, the historical process is largely a communal one, with eyewitness accounts, hearsay, reminiscences, and occasionally visions, dreams, and hallucinations crafted into narrative oral traditions which are performed and transmitted through generations.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In oral traditions time is sometimes mythical and social, and ancestors were considered historical actors.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Mind and memory shapes traditions, as events are condensed over time and crystallise into clichés.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Oral tradition can be exoteric or esoteric.
[src:banana/africa-p01] It speaks to people according to their understanding, unveiling itself in accordance with their aptitudes.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Africa is considered by most paleoanthropologists to be the oldest inhabited territory on Earth, with the Human species originating from the continent.
[src:banana/africa-p01] During the mid-20th century, anthropologists discovered many fossils and evidence of human occupation perhaps as early as seven million years ago ("Before Present"; BP).
[src:banana/africa-p01] Fossil remains of several species of early apelike humans thought to have evolved into modern humans, such as *Australopithecus afarensis* radiometrically dated to approximately 3.9–3.0 million years BP, *Paranthropus boisei* (c.
[src:banana/africa-p01] 2.3–1.4 million years BP) and *Homo ergaster* (c.
[src:banana/africa-p01] 1.9 million–600,000 years BP) have been discovered.
[src:banana/africa-p01] After the evolution of *Homo sapiens* approximately 350,000 to 260,000 years BP in Africa, the continent was mainly populated by groups of hunter-gatherers.
[src:banana/africa-p01] These first modern humans left Africa and populated the rest of the globe during the Out of Africa II migration dated to approximately 50,000 years BP, exiting the continent either across Bab-el-Mandeb over the Red Sea, the Strait of Gibraltar in Morocco, or the Isthmus of Suez in Egypt.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Other migrations of modern humans within the African continent have been dated to that time, with evidence of early human settlement found in Southern Africa, Southeast Africa, North Africa, and the Sahara.
[src:banana/africa-p01] However, the warming and drying climate meant that by 5,000 BC, the Sahara region was becoming increasingly dry and hostile.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Around 3500 BC, due to a tilt in the Earth's orbit, the Sahara experienced a period of rapid desertification.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The domestication of cattle in Africa preceded agriculture and seems to have existed alongside hunter-gatherer cultures.
[src:banana/africa-p01] It is speculated that by 6,000 BC, cattle were domesticated in North Africa.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In West Africa, a wet phase ushered in an expanding rainforest and wooded savanna from Senegal to Cameroon.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Between 9,000 and 5,000 BC, Niger–Congo speakers domesticated the oil palm and raffia palm.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Black-eyed peas and voandzeia (African groundnuts), were domesticated, followed by okra and kola nuts.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Since most of the plants grew in the forest, the Niger–Congo speakers invented polished stone axes for clearing forest.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Pygmies are thought to have inhabited Central Africa for many millennia, splitting into eastern and western groups around 5,000 BP.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Over 150,000 BP, there was an early dispersal of anatomically modern humans to Southern Africa, equated with the modern-day Khoisan who have preserved their traditional hunter-gatherer way of life.
[src:banana/africa-p01] From 3500 BC, nomes (ruled by nomarchs) coalesced to form the kingdoms of Lower Egypt and Upper Egypt in northeast Africa.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Around 3100 BC Upper Egypt conquered Lower Egypt to unify Egypt under the 1st dynasty, with the process of consolidation and assimilation completed by the time of the 3rd dynasty who formed the Old Kingdom of Egypt in 2686 BC.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The Kingdom of Kerma emerged around this time to become the dominant force in Nubia, controlling territory as large as Egypt between the 1st and 4th cataracts of the Nile.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The height of the Old Kingdom saw the construction of many great pyramids, though under the 6th dynasty power gradually decentralised to the nomarchs, culminating in the disintegration of the kingdom, exacerbated by drought and famine.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Around 2055 BC, the 11th dynasty, based in Thebes, conquered the others to form the Middle Kingdom of Egypt, and the 12th dynasty expanded into Lower Nubia at the expense of Kerma.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Around 1700 BC, the Middle Kingdom fractured in two, and the Hyksos (a militaristic people from Palestine) invaded and conquered Lower Egypt, while Kerma coordinated invasions deep into Egypt to reach its greatest extent.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In 1550 BC, the 18th dynasty expelled the Hyksos, and established the New Kingdom of Egypt.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The New Kingdom conquered the Levant from the Canaanites, Mittani, Amorites, and Hittites, and extinguished Kerma, incorporating Nubia into the empire, and sending the Egyptian empire into its golden age.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Internal struggles, drought, famine, and invasions by a confederation of seafaring peoples contributed to the New Kingdom's collapse in 1069 BC.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The New Kingdom's collapse liberated the Kingdom of Kush in Nubia, which manoeuvred into power in Upper Egypt and conquered Lower Egypt in 754 BC to form the Kushite Empire.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The Kushites ruled for a century and oversaw a revival in pyramid building, until they were driven out of Egypt by the Assyrians in 663 BC in reprisal for their expansion towards the Assyrian Empire.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The Assyrians installed a puppet dynasty that later gained independence and once more unified Egypt, until it was conquered by the Achaemenid Empire in 525 BC.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Egypt briefly regained independence from the Achaemenids under the 28th dynasty from 404 to 343 BC.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The conquest of Achaemenid Egypt by Alexander the Great in 332 BC marked the beginning of Hellenistic rule and the installation of the Macedonian Ptolemaic dynasty in Egypt.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The Ptolemaics lost their holdings outside of Africa to the Seleucids in the Syrian Wars, expanded into Cyrenaica, and briefly occupied part of Kush in the 3rd century BC.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In the 1st century BC, Ptolemaic Egypt became entangled in a Roman civil war, leading to its conquest by the Romans in 30 BC.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Kush persisted as a major regional power until, having been weakened from internal rebellion amid worsening climatic conditions, invasions by Aksum and the Noba caused their disintegration into Makuria, Alodia, and Nobatia around the 5th century AD.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In the Horn of Africa, there was the Land of Punt, a kingdom on the Red Sea which was a close trading partner of Ancient Egypt in the 3rd and 2nd millennia BC.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Rodolfo Fattovich equated it to the Gash Group in the Sudanese-Eritrean lowlands, and some scholars have hypothesised modern-day Somalia, while Kenneth Kitchen and Felix Chami locate it on Zanzibar Island.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In the Eritrean-Ethiopian Highlands, the kingdom of dʿmt rose c.
[src:banana/africa-p01] 980 BC as the region was incorporated into global trading networks, and it exhibited Sabaean influences which most scholars attribute to a small migration of Sabaeans and their assimilation.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Several scholars consider there to have been other contemporaneous states, and dʿmt's collapse in the mid-1st century BC saw the region inhabited by small polities.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Modern-day Somalia was inhabited by nomadic pastoralists, and along the Horn's coast there were many ancient Somali city-states that thrived off of the wider Red Sea trade, and enjoyed a lucrative monopoly on cinnamon from Ancient India due to their freedom from Roman interference.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In the 1st century AD, the Kingdom of Aksum rose from a city-state to rule much of the northern Ethiopian-Eritrean Highlands and the Red Sea port of Adulis.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Aksum was described as one of the four great powers by Persian prophet Mani in the 3rd century.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Aksum's king converted from traditional religion to Christianity in the 4th century, gradually followed by the population.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In the 6th century, Aksum conquered South Arabia, though struggled to maintain control over it, and began to gradually lose its dominance over Red Sea trade to Persians and Arabs.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Northwest Africa (the Maghreb) was inhabited by Berber semi-nomadic pastoralists.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In the 1st millennium BC, Phoenician migration and settlement came in search for precious metals in the Gulf of Tunis.
[src:banana/africa-p01] This grew into Ancient Carthage after gaining independence from Phoenicia in the 6th century BC, and they built an extensive trading empire with a strict mercantile network.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Carthage's collapse and conquest by Rome in the Punic Wars (3rd and 2nd centuries BC) saw Numidia and Mauretania become major powers in the Maghreb.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Towards the end of the 2nd century BC Mauretania fought alongside Numidia's Jugurtha against the Romans in the Jugurthine War after he had usurped the Numidian throne from a Roman ally.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Together they inflicted heavy casualties, with the war only ending inconclusively when Mauretania's Bocchus I sold out Jugurtha to the Romans.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Around the turn of the millennium, both came under direct Roman rule.
[src:banana/africa-p01] While traditional religion predominated among Berbers, some people converted to Christianity.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In the 5th century AD the Vandals conquered Roman Africa before the fall of Rome, though the province was reconquered by the Byzantines a century later.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Large swathes of indigenous peoples regained self-governance in Masuna and its numerous successor polities in the Maghreb, including the kingdoms of Ouarsenis, Aurès, and Altava.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In the western Sahel the rise of settled communities occurred largely as a result of the domestication of millet and of sorghum, and cattle pastoralism began c.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Extensive east-west belts of deserts, grasslands, and forests from north to south were crucial for the moulding of their respective societies and meant that symbiotic trade relations developed in response to the differing environments.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Beginning around 4000 BC, the Tichitt culture in modern-day Mauritania and Mali is the oldest known complexly organised society in West Africa, while others included the Kintampo culture in modern-day Ghana, the Nok culture in modern-day Nigeria, and the Daima culture around Lake Chad.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Towards the end of the 3rd century AD, a wet period in the Sahel created areas for human habitation and exploitation that had not been habitable for the best part of a millennium.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The Ghana Empire (also called *Wagadu*) rose out of the Tichitt culture, growing wealthy following the introduction of the camel to the western Sahel, which revolutionised the trans-Saharan trade that linked their capital and Aoudaghost with Tahert and Sijilmasa in North Africa.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Soninke tradition holds that the final founding of Wagadu occurred after Dinga did a deal with Bida, a serpent deity who was guarding a well, to sacrifice one maiden a year in exchange for assurance regarding plenty of rainfall and gold supply.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Based on large tumuli scattered across West Africa dating to this period, several scholars have speculated that there were further simultaneous and preceding states relative to Wagadu.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In the Grasslands of northwestern Cameroon, Bantu-speaking agriculturalists started to gradually migrate south sometime between 5000 BC and 3000 BC.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Despite intensive research, the cause of the migrations, and that of the directions taken, is still unclear, however there is consensus that there were multiple dispersal events.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Around 1500 BC, Bantu speakers reached central Cameroon.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The 'Western Stream' likely followed the coast and the major rivers of the Congo system southwards to reach the southern fringe of the Congolian Rainforest around 500 BC (some may have used the sea to circumvent the rainforest).
[src:banana/africa-p01] Their arrival coincided with the spread of iron metallurgy through Central Africa.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Meanwhile, the 'Eastern Stream' travelled either the northern fringe of the rainforest or the Ubangi River eastwards, and reached just west of Lake Victoria around 500 BC.
[src:banana/africa-p01] While there, Bantu speakers adopted iron metallurgy from Cushitic speakers already present, and coexisted with them.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Dispersal from the Great Lakes region occurred in two more streams.
[src:banana/africa-p01] One went west to meet the Western Stream in the DR Congo and Angola, while the other went south and spread across Eastern and Southern Africa.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Around the turn of the millennium, Bantu speakers reached central modern-day Tanzania and near Dar es Salaam, before rapidly moving southwards along the coast to reach modern-day Kwazulu Natal in South Africa around the 3rd century AD.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Throughout this, Bantu speakers displaced, replaced, or intermarried with and absorbed hunter-gatherer and agricultural groups.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In the 7th and 8th centuries, as part of the Arab conquests which sought to spread Islamic rule, the Rashidun and Umayyad caliphates conquered North Africa at the expense of the Byzantine Empire and Berber leaders such as Kusaila and Kahina.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Large numbers of Berber and Coptic people willingly converted to Islam, and followers of Abrahamic religions ('People of the Book') were protected, though followers of Berber traditional religion were violently oppressed.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In the 8th century the Berber Revolt rocked the Caliphate and Berber dynasties took control over the Maghreb, while the Tulunids briefly controlled Egypt.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In the 10th century, the Fatimids rose to power in modern-day Tunisia, established a rival caliphate, and conquered Egypt, before expanding into the Middle East.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In the 11th century the Almoravids conquered the Maghreb and intervened in the Christian reconquest of Iberia.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Saladin, a Fatimid vizier, usurped power in the 12th century and established the Ayyubid dynasty which restored Egyptian prestige, while the Almohad revolution deposed the Almoravids to the east.
[src:banana/africa-p01] After Christian gains in Iberia in the 13th century, the Almohads disintegrated into the Marinids, Zayyanids, and Hafsids in modern-day Morocco, Algeria, and Tunisia respectively.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In the face of Mongol expansion, Mamluk generals seized power in Egypt and expanded into the Middle East.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In the early-16th century, the Ottoman Empire rapidly conquered North Africa (save for Morocco, now under Saadi rule) to counter Spanish expansionism.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In the following centuries, over a million Europeans are estimated to have been captured and enslaved by Barbary corsairs.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The Ottoman regencies became more independent during the 18th century.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In the central Sahel around Lake Chad, the Kanem–Bornu Empire ruled from the 6th century, and projected power over the Hausa Kingdoms.
[src:banana/africa-p01] To the east during 7th century, Makuria conquered Nobatia to become the dominant power in the region and resisted Muslim expansion.
[src:banana/africa-p01] They later entered a severe decline following civil war and Arab migrations to the Sudan and had disintegrated by the 15th century, giving rise to the Funj Sultanate.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The Tunjur empire's collapse in the central Sudan saw the rise of the Bagirmi, Wadai, and Darfur sultanates, which frequently raided the populations to their south for slaves.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In the Horn of Africa, Aksum lost control of the Red Sea, and its isolation from Christendom caused Ethiopian society to introspect and take inspiration from the Old Testament.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Islamised Beja invaded the Ethiopian Highlands, forcing Aksum to migrate south, where, according to tradition, Aksum's expansion was met by a Jewish or traditionalist queen who destroyed the state c.
[src:banana/africa-p01] During the 13th century, hegemony in the Horn was contested by the Christian Zagwe, the Muslims of Shewa, and the traditionalist Damot; the Solomonic dynasty overthrew the Zagwe to found the Ethiopian Empire, while Shewa was replaced by Ifat.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Soon after, Ethiopia conquered Damot and the Muslim states, entering into a 'golden age'.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In the 16th century Muslims united behind Adal in *jihad* to reconquer the Muslim lands and occupy Ethiopia, until, with Portuguese assistance, Ethiopia counter-attacked and its sovereignty was restored in a reduced state.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The 16th and 17th centuries also saw Oromo invasions into the Horn, weakening Ethiopia further and causing the collapse of Adal, while Ajuran on the east coast also disintegrated.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Ethiopia briefly consolidated its authority in the late-17th century, though the turn of the century saw fragmentation and gradually-increasing anarchy, which continued throughout the 18th century.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In the Sahel region of West Africa, the Ghana Empire formed from between the 2nd and 8th centuries, while from the 7th century the Gao Empire ruled to its east.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Almoravid capture of royal Aoudaghost led to Ghana's conversion to Islam in the 11th century, and climatic changes led to Ghana's conquest by its vassal Sosso in the 13th century.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Sosso was quickly overthrown by the Mali Empire who conquered Gao and dominated the trans-Saharan trade.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The Mossi Kingdoms were established to its south.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The 15th century saw the crumbling of the Mali Empire, with the dominant power in the region becoming the Songhai Empire centered on Gao.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Weakened by internal conflict, in 1591 Gao was conquered by Morocco, and the political vacuum came to be filled by the Segou Empire and several other states.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The once lucrative trans-Saharan trade gradually lost its prominence to the coastal Atlantic trade with Europeans, and the following centuries saw many droughts, famines, and epidemics.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In the forest regions of West Africa, various kingdoms and empires flourished, such as the Yoruba empires of Ife and Oyo, the Igbo Kingdom of Nri, the Edo Kingdom of Benin (famous for its art), the Dagomba Kingdom of Dagbon, and the Akan kingdoms of Bonoman and Adanse.
[src:banana/africa-p01] They came into contact with the Portuguese in the 15th century which saw the start of the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The Asante Empire was established in present-day Ghana.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Between 1515 and 1800, 8 million Africans were exported in the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In the western Congo Basin by the 13th century there were three main confederations of states: the Seven Kingdoms, Mpemba, and one led by Vungu.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In the 14th century the Kingdom of Kongo emerged and dominated the region, with the Tio Kingdom to its north and Mwene Muji to its northeast.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Over the course of the late-16th and 17th centuries, the Portuguese sought to conquer Ndongo (allied to Matamba) in the Angolan Wars; despite fierce resistance from Queen Nzinga, and brief occupation of Luanda by the Dutch (allied to Kongo), Portugal controlled most of Ndongo by the 1670s.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The late-17th century saw Kongo fragment between royal houses as several vassals broke away; by the time of Kongo's restoration in 1709, it had ceased being the dominant regional power.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Also during the 17th century, in the textile-producing northeast, the Boma, Yaka, and possibly the Kuba and Pende kingdoms broke away from Mwene Muji.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In the eastern Congo Basin, farmers, fishermen, and hunters (often Pygmies) built symbiotic relations.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Jan Vansina wrote that in the southern savanna 'lords of the land' held priestly roles due to their special relationship with the spirits of the land, and held sway over multiple villages, effectively ruling embryonic kingdoms.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Accordingly, as lineages grew, authority was opportunistically absorbed or incorporated by force.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The centre of the Luba Empire is yet to undergo archaeological research, meaning knowledge about its rise is limited; its foundation is typically dated to the 14th/15th centuries, though scholarly estimates range from the 8th to 17th centuries.
[src:banana/africa-p01] A Lunda state formed in the Nkalany Valley (estimates range from c.
[src:banana/africa-p01] 1700), in the 18th century, Lunda rapidly expanded into an extensive commonwealth across the southern savanna, using the institutions of perpetual kinship and positional succession to incorporate peoples.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Meanwhile, Luba expanded its number of tributaries, in some cases using its widely acknowledged prestige to intervene in succession disputes and distribute ritually-powerful royal regalia related to *bulopwe* (sacred kingship), in other cases using conquest.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In the northern Great Lakes, the Empire of Kitara rose around the 11th century, famed for its oral traditions.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Peter Robertshaw considered its rulers (the Chwezi) to have been religious leaders who utilised networks of hill-top shrines to project authority.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Around 1500, severe droughts and famine destabilised the region, occurring again during the early-17th and 18th centuries.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Luo-speaking peoples migrated from the Upper Nile basin into modern-day Uganda, and a Biito dynasty replaced the Chwezi in Bunyoro-Kitara.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Over the following centuries, the kingdoms of Bunyoro-Kitara, Buganda, and Rwanda struggled for hegemony among others.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Throughout the 16th and 17th centuries, Bunyoro raided states to the south such as Nkore and Rwanda.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Mpororo rose and fragmented during the 18th century, while Buganda rapidly expanded at the expense of Bunyoro to become the major power in the region.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The East African interior was inhabited by pastoralist Cushitic and Nilotic speakers, along with Bantu speakers who continued to expand and adapt to their lands while absorbing the former two; the 17th century saw the establishment of tributary systems that stabilised the region.
[src:banana/africa-p01] On the Swahili coast the Swahili city-states thrived off of the Indian Ocean trade and gradually Islamized, giving rise to the Kilwa Sultanate from the 10th century.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In the 15th century, trade routes for Zimbabwean gold shifted north, weakening Kilwa.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The Portuguese arrived at the coast soon after, and exploited divisions between coastal city-states to gain control over them while utilising a powerful navy.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In the 17th and 18th centuries, Lamu-Swahili cities rebelled against the Portuguese and allied the Omani Empire which supplanted Portuguese rule.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Madagascar was settled by Austronesian peoples between the 5th and 7th centuries, as societies organized at the behest of *hasina* and competed over with one another over the island's estuaries and bridgeheads.
[src:banana/africa-p01] From around the 15th century, southern Madagascar became integrated into global trade; the Sakalava Empire rose to dominate west-coastal trade, accompanied by numerous other states, and the island saw several failed European colonial ventures.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In Southern Africa, an early kingdom was Mapungubwe, which collapsed c.
[src:banana/africa-p01] 1300 as Great Zimbabwe, with its monumental dry-stone walls, rose to become the region's main political and economic centre.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Following shifting trade routes north to the Zambezi and unclear circumstances, Great Zimbabwe entered into decline and was succeeded by the Mutapa Empire and Kingdom of Butua in the 15th century.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Mutapa was briefly vassalised by the Portuguese in the 17th century, the latter-half of which saw widespread famine and disease, until Changamire Dombo revolted in the 1680s, conquered Butua to found the Rozvi Empire, and expelled all Portuguese from the Zimbabwean Plateau.
[src:banana/africa-p01] North of the Zambezi, Maravi around Lake Malawi expanded in the 17th century, but the collapse of its succession system in the 18th century precipitated its disintegration.
[src:banana/africa-p01] By the late-1st millennium CE, Bantu-speaking farmers populated most of Southern Africa's cultivable savannas, reaching southwards to the Kei River; they traded goods such as livestock, grain, and metal tools between communities and with hunter-gatherers.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Further south, the Dutch began colonizing the western Cape in the 17th century, and Britain seized control of the colony around the turn of the 19th century.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In the late-18th century, the interplay of pre-existing trends of political centralization with the effects of international trade, environmental instability, and European colonisation set the *Mfecane* ("Crushing") in motion, as various African states were founded.
[src:banana/africa-p01] By the turn of the 19th century, many of Africa's economic and political structures were unstable and brittle as a result of long-term effects of the slave trade.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In Egypt Muhammad Ali led a national movement to seize power from Ottoman suzerainty, instituting sweeping reforms and greatly strengthening Egyptian power by militaristic expansion.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Meanwhile, in West Africa the Fula *jihad*s, which had been gaining momentum throughout the 18th century, culminated in the establishment of the expansive Sokoto and Hamdullahi caliphates.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In the Horn, Ethiopia underwent reforms, seeking to revive the imperial state, something that was later achieved by Menelik II's conquests.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In Southern Africa the *Mfecane* propelled large long-distance migrations that caused widespread disruption across the vast region, while several Boer republics were founded.
[src:banana/africa-p01] European campaigns to abolish the Atlantic slave trade led to supply refocusing on internal markets and saw the rapid growth of the Indian Ocean slave trade.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Across the continent many rulers attempted reforms and indigenous forms of 'modernisation', however these efforts were consistently undermined by European traders and missionaries as the tide of European encroachment rose.
[src:banana/africa-p01] For 400 years, European nations had mainly limited their involvement to trading stations on the African coast, with few daring to venture inland.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The Industrial Revolution in Europe produced several technological innovations which assisted them in overcoming this 400-year pattern.
[src:banana/africa-p01] One was the development of repeating rifles, which were easier and quicker to load than muskets.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Maxim developed the maxim gun, the model of the modern-day machine gun.
[src:banana/africa-p01] European states kept these weapons largely among themselves by refusing to sell these weapons to African leaders.
[src:banana/africa-p01] African germs took numerous European lives and deterred permanent settlements.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Diseases such as yellow fever, sleeping sickness, yaws, and leprosy made Africa a very inhospitable place for Europeans.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The deadliest disease was malaria, endemic throughout Tropical Africa.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In 1854, the discovery of quinine and other medical innovations helped to make conquest and colonisation in Africa possible.
[src:banana/africa-p01] There were strong motives for the conquest of Africa.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Raw materials were needed for European factories, and free trade was championed to prevent Africans from regulating their economies.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Prestige and imperial rivalries were at play.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Acquiring African colonies would show rivals that a nation was powerful and significant.
[src:banana/africa-p01] These contextual factors forged the Scramble for Africa; during the late-19th and early-20th centuries the European powers partitioned and conquered almost all of Africa despite fierce resistance (only Ethiopia and Liberia remained independent).
[src:banana/africa-p01] Traditional leaders were incorporated into the colonial regimes as a form of indirect rule to extract human and natural resources and curb organized resistance.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Colonial borders were drawn unilaterally by the Europeans, often cutting across bonds of kinship, language, culture, and established routes, and sometimes incorporating groups who previously had little in common.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The threat to trade routes was mitigated by poor policing and African entrepreneurs (viewed as smugglers) who exploited the differing tax and legal schemes.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The first few decades of European colonialism saw intense violence, disorder, and atrocities, such as that of the Congo Free State, German South West Africa, and French Algeria, with the late colonial period relatively peaceful in comparison.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Colonial rule had wide-reaching effects on African societies, such as the spread of Christianity as part of the 'civilising mission'.
[src:banana/africa-p01] African culture was strongly denigrated and persecuted, as pervasive racial discrimination deepened the scars of humiliation.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Imperial rule by Europeans continued until after the conclusion of World War II, when almost all remaining colonial territories gradually obtained formal independence.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Independence movements in Africa gained momentum following World War II, which left the major European powers weakened.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In 1951, Libya, a former Italian colony, gained independence.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In 1956, Tunisia and Morocco won their independence from France.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Ghana followed suit the next year (March 1957), becoming the first of the sub-Saharan colonies to be granted independence.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Over the next decade, waves of decolonisation took place across the continent, culminating in the 1960 Year of Africa and the establishment of the Organisation of African Unity in 1963.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Portugal's overseas presence in sub-Saharan Africa (most notably in Angola, Cape Verde, Mozambique, Guinea-Bissau, and São Tomé and Príncipe) lasted from the 16th century to 1975, after the Estado Novo regime was overthrown in a military coup in Lisbon.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Rhodesia unilaterally declared independence from the United Kingdom in 1965, under the white minority government of Ian Smith, but was not internationally recognised as an independent state (as Zimbabwe) until 1980, when black nationalists gained power after a bitter guerrilla war.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Although South Africa was one of the first African countries to gain independence, the state remained under the control of the country's white minority, initially through qualified voting rights and from 1956 by a system of racial segregation known as apartheid, until 1994.
[src:banana/africa-p01] As of 2025, Africa contains 54 sovereign countries.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Since independence, African states have frequently been hampered by instability, corruption, violence, and authoritarianism.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The vast majority of African states are republics that operate under some form of the presidential system of rule.
[src:banana/africa-p01] However, few of them have been able to sustain democratic governments on a permanent basis—per the criteria laid out by Lührmann et al.
[src:banana/africa-p01] (2018), only Botswana and Mauritius have been consistently democratic for the entirety of their post-colonial history.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Most African countries have experienced several coups or periods of military dictatorship.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Between 1990 and 2018, though, the continent as a whole has trended towards more democratic governance.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Upon independence an overwhelming majority of Africans lived in extreme poverty.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The continent suffered from the lack of infrastructural or industrial development under colonial rule, along with political instability.
[src:banana/africa-p01] With limited financial resources or access to global markets, relatively stable countries such as Kenya still experienced only very slow economic development.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Only a handful of African countries succeeded in obtaining rapid economic growth prior to 1990.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Exceptions include Libya and Equatorial Guinea, both of which possess large oil reserves.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Instability throughout the continent after decolonisation resulted primarily from marginalisation of ethnic groups, and corruption.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Faced with increasingly frequent and severe violence, military rule was widely accepted by the population of many countries as means to maintain order, and during the 1970s and 1980s a majority of African countries were controlled by military dictatorships.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Territorial disputes between nations and rebellions by groups seeking independence were also common in independent African states.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The most devastating of these was the Nigerian Civil War, fought between government forces and an Igbo separatist republic, which resulted in a famine that killed 1–2 million people.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Two civil wars in Sudan, the first lasting from 1955 to 1972 and the second from 1983 to 2005, collectively killed around 3 million.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Both were fought primarily on ethnic and religious lines.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Cold War conflicts between the United States and the Soviet Union also contributed to instability.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Both the Soviet Union and the United States offered considerable incentives to African political and military leaders who aligned themselves with the superpowers' foreign policy.
[src:banana/africa-p01] As an example, during the Angolan Civil War, the Soviet and Cuban aligned MPLA and the American aligned UNITA received the vast majority of their military and political support from these countries.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Many African countries became highly dependent on foreign aid.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The sudden loss of both Soviet and American aid at the end of the Cold War and fall of the USSR resulted in severe economic and political turmoil in the countries most dependent on foreign support.
[src:banana/africa-p01] There was a major famine in Ethiopia between 1983 and 1985, killing up to 1.2 million people, which most historians attribute primarily to the forced relocation of farmworkers and seizure of grain by the communist Derg government, further exacerbated by the civil war.
[src:banana/africa-p01] In 1994 a genocide in Rwanda resulted in up to 800,000 deaths, added to a severe refugee crisis and fuelled the rise of militia groups in neighbouring countries.
[src:banana/africa-p01] This contributed to the outbreak of the first and second Congo Wars, which were the most devastating military conflicts in modern Africa, with up to 5.5 million deaths, making it by far the deadliest conflict in modern African history and one of the costliest wars in human history.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Various conflicts between various insurgent groups and governments continue.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Since 2003, there has been an ongoing conflict in Darfur (Sudan), which peaked in intensity from 2003 to 2005 with notable spikes in violence in 2007 and 2013–15, killing around 300,000 people total.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The Boko Haram Insurgency primarily within Nigeria (with considerable fighting in Niger, Chad, and Cameroon as well) has killed around 350,000 people since 2009.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Most African conflicts have been reduced to low-intensity conflicts as of 2022.
[src:banana/africa-p01] However, the Tigray War from 2020 to 2022 killed an estimated 300,000–500,000 people, primarily due to famine.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Overall though, violence across Africa has greatly declined in the 21st century, with the end of civil wars in Angola, Sierra Leone, and Algeria in 2002, Liberia in 2003, and Sudan and Burundi in 2005.
[src:banana/africa-p01] The Second Congo War, which involved 9 countries and several insurgent groups, ended in 2003.
[src:banana/africa-p01] This decline in violence coincided with many countries abandoning communist-style command economies and opening up for market reforms, which over the course of the 1990s and 2000s promoted the establishment of permanent, peaceful trade between neighbouring countries (see Capitalist peace).
[src:banana/africa-p01] Improved stability and economic reforms have led to a great increase in foreign investment into many African nations, mainly from China, which further spurred economic growth.
[src:banana/africa-p01] Between 2000 and 2014, annual GDP growth in sub-Saharan Africa averaged 5.02%, doubling its total GDP from $811 billion to $1.63 trillion (constant 2015 USD).
[src:banana/africa-p01] North Africa experienced comparable growth rates.
[src:banana/africa-p01] A significant part of this growth can also be attributed to the facilitated diffusion of information technologies and specifically the mobile telephone.
[src:banana/africa-p01] While several individual countries have maintained high growth rates, since 2014 overall growth has considerably slowed, primarily as a result of falling commodity prices, continued lack of industrialisation, and epidemics such as Ebola and COVID-19.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Africa is the largest of the three great southward projections from the largest landmass of the Earth.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Separated from Europe by the Mediterranean Sea, it is joined to Asia at its northeast extremity by the Isthmus of Suez (transected by the Suez Canal), 163 km (101 mi) wide.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Geopolitically, Egypt's Sinai Peninsula east of the Suez Canal is often considered part of Africa as well.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The coastline is 26,000 km (16,000 mi) long, and the absence of deep indentations of the shore is illustrated by the fact that Europe, which covers only 10,400,000 km2 (4,000,000 sq mi) – about a third of the surface of Africa – has a coastline of 32,000 km (20,000 mi).
[src:banana/africa-p02] From the most northerly point, Ras ben Sakka in Tunisia (37°21' N), to the most southerly point, Cape Agulhas in South Africa (34°51'15" S), is a distance of approximately 8,000 km (5,000 mi).
[src:banana/africa-p02] Cape Verde, 17°33'22" W, the westernmost point, is a distance of approximately 7,400 km (4,600 mi) to Ras Hafun, 51°27'52" E, the most easterly projection that neighbours Cape Guardafui, the tip of the Horn of Africa.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Africa's largest country is Algeria, and its smallest country is Seychelles, an archipelago off the east coast.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The smallest nation on the continental mainland is The Gambia.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The African plate, also known as the Nubian plate, is a major tectonic plate that includes most of the continent of Africa (except for its easternmost part) and the adjacent oceanic crust to the west and south.
[src:banana/africa-p02] It also includes a narrow strip of Western Asia along the Mediterranean Sea, including much of Israel, Palestine and Lebanon.
[src:banana/africa-p02] It is bounded by the North American plate and South American plate to the west (separated by the Mid-Atlantic Ridge); the Arabian plate and Somali plate to the east; the Eurasian plate, Aegean Sea plate and Anatolian plate to the north; and the Antarctic plate to the south.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Between 60 million years ago and 10 million years ago, the Somali plate began rifting from the African plate along the East African Rift.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Since the continent of Africa consists of crust from both the African and the Somali plates, some literature refers to the African plate as the *Nubian plate* to distinguish it from the continent as a whole.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The climate of Africa ranges from tropical to subarctic on its highest peaks.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Its northern half is primarily desert, or arid, while its central and southern areas contain both savanna plains and dense jungle (rainforest) regions.
[src:banana/africa-p02] In between, there is a convergence, where vegetation patterns such as sahel and steppe dominate.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Africa is the hottest continent on Earth and 60% of the entire land surface consists of drylands and deserts.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The record for the highest-ever recorded temperature, in Libya in 1922 (58 °C (136 °F)), was discredited in 2013.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Climate change in Africa is a serious threat because the continent is one of the most vulnerable regions to the effects of climate change, despite being responsible for less than 4% of global greenhouse emissions.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Climate change is causing increasingly erratic rainfall patterns, more frequent extreme weather events such as droughts, floods, and rising sea-surface temperatures across the continent.
[src:banana/africa-p02] These changes threaten food and water security, biodiversity, public health, and economic development.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Africa is currently warming faster than the rest of the world on average.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Climate change intensifies existing socioeconomic vulnerabilities.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Large segments of the African population depend on climate-sensitive livelihoods such as agriculture (55 - 62% of the workforce in sub-Saharan Africa) and already live in poverty, heightening their exposure to shocks.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Health outcomes worsen as heat stress, vector-borne diseases (such as malaria and dengue), and malnutrition become more prevalent.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Over half (56%) of the over 2,000 recorded public health incidents in Africa between 2001 and 2021 were connected to climate change.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Resource scarcity contributes to displacement and conflict, particularly in fragile regions.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Urban areas, often characterized by informal settlements, face heightened risks from flooding and extreme heat.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Africa has over 3,000 protected areas, with 198 marine protected areas, 50 biosphere reserves, and 80 wetlands reserves.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Significant habitat destruction, increases in human population and poaching are reducing Africa's biological diversity and arable land.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Human encroachment, civil unrest and the introduction of non-native species threaten biodiversity in Africa.
[src:banana/africa-p02] This has been exacerbated by administrative problems, inadequate personnel and funding problems.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Deforestation is affecting Africa at twice the world rate, according to the United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP).
[src:banana/africa-p02] The deforestation rate of 4.08 million hectares in 2000–2015 declined to 3.45 million ha per year in 2015–2025.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Some sources claim that approximately 90% of the original, virgin forests in West Africa have been destroyed.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Over 90% of Madagascar's original forests have been destroyed since the arrival of humans 2000 years ago.
[src:banana/africa-p02] About 65% of Africa's agricultural land suffers from soil degradation.
[src:banana/africa-p02] It is also home to a variety of "jungle" animals including snakes and primates and aquatic life such as crocodiles and amphibians.
[src:banana/africa-p02] In addition, Africa has the largest number of megafauna species, as it was least affected by the extinction of the Pleistocene megafauna.
[src:banana/africa-p02] African environmental problems are problems caused by the direct and indirect human impacts on the natural environment and affect humans and nearly all forms of life in Africa.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Issues include deforestation, soil degradation, air pollution, water pollution, coastal erosion, garbage pollution, climate change, Oil spills, Biodiversity loss, and water scarcity (resulting in problems with access to safe water supply and sanitation).
[src:banana/africa-p02] These issues result in environmental conflict and are connected to broader social struggles for democracy and sovereignty.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The scarcity of climate adaptation techniques in Africa makes it the least resilient continent to climate change.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The African Union (AU) is a continental union consisting of 55 member states.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The union was formed, with Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, as its headquarters, on 26 June 2001.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The union was officially established on 9 July 2002 as a successor to the Organisation of African Unity (OAU).
[src:banana/africa-p02] In July 2004, the African Union's Pan-African Parliament (PAP) was relocated to Midrand, in South Africa, but the African Commission on Human and Peoples' Rights remained in Addis Ababa.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The African Union, not to be confused with the AU Commission, is formed by the Constitutive Act of the African Union, which aims to transform the African Economic Community, a federated commonwealth, into a state under established international conventions.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The African Union has a parliamentary government, known as the African Union Government, consisting of legislative, judicial and executive organs.
[src:banana/africa-p02] It is led by the African Union President and Head of State, who is also the President of the Pan-African Parliament.
[src:banana/africa-p02] A person becomes AU President by being elected to the PAP, and subsequently gaining majority support in the PAP.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The government of the AU consists of all-union, regional, state, and municipal authorities, as well as hundreds of institutions, that together manage the day-to-day affairs of the institution.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Extensive human rights abuses still occur in several parts of Africa, often under the oversight of the state.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Most of such violations occur for political reasons, often as a side effect of civil war.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Countries where major human rights violations have been reported in recent times include the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Sierra Leone, Liberia, Sudan, Zimbabwe, and Ivory Coast.
[src:banana/africa-p02] African nations have made great efforts to respect international borders as inviolate for a long time.
[src:banana/africa-p02] For example, the Organization of African Unity (OAU), which was established in 1963 and replaced by the African Union in 2002, set the respect for the territorial integrity of each country as one of its principles in OAU Charter.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Indeed, compared with the formation of European countries, there have been fewer international conflicts in Africa for changing the borders, which has influenced country formation there and has enabled some countries to survive that might have been defeated and absorbed by others.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Yet international conflicts have played out by support for proxy armies or rebel movements.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Many states have experienced civil wars: including Rwanda, Sudan, Angola, Sierra Leone, Congo, Liberia, Ethiopia and Somalia.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Wars of national liberation also often took up a Marxist, Marxist–Leninist, or Maoist character in ideological terms, where the independence of African nations was raised in Marxian terms.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Early examples included the Union of the Peoples of Cameroon armed movement against French colonialism, a Marxist–Leninist insurgency, followed by similar movements in Congo (the Simba Rebellion).
[src:banana/africa-p02] Che Guevara participated in the latter, and opined in 1967 that Africa was not ready for revolution.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Despite this, in Zanzibar before and after unification with Tanzania, forms of socialism took hold.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Even after 1990, there are some examples of Military Marxism, such as a militia established by Ernest Wamba-dia-Wamba in Eastern Congo in the 1990s.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The countries in this table are categorised according to the scheme for geographic subregions used by the United Nations, and data included are per sources in cross-referenced articles.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Where they differ, provisos are clearly indicated.
[src:banana/africa-p02] This list contains nine territories that are administered as incorporated areas of a primarily non-African country but that belong geographically to the African continent.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The continent's total nominal GDP remains behind that of several individual countries, including the United States, China, Japan, Germany, the United Kingdom, India and France.
[src:banana/africa-p02] According to the United Nations' Human Development Report in 2003, the bottom 24 ranked nations (151st to 175th) were all African.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Poverty, illiteracy, malnutrition, inadequate water supply and sanitation, and poor health affect a large proportion of the people who reside on the African continent.
[src:banana/africa-p02] In August 2008, the World Bank announced revised global poverty estimates based on a new international poverty line of $1.25 per day (versus the previous measure of $1.00).
[src:banana/africa-p02] Eighty-one percent of the sub-Saharan African population was living on less than $2.50 (PPP) per day in 2005, compared with 86% for India.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Sub-Saharan Africa is the least successful region of the world in reducing poverty ($1.25 per day); some 50% of the population living in poverty in 1981 (200 million people), a figure that rose to 58% in 1996 before dropping to 50% in 2005 (380 million people).
[src:banana/africa-p02] The average poor person in sub-Saharan Africa is estimated to live on only 70 cents per day, and was poorer in 2003 than in 1973, indicating increasing poverty in some areas.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Some of it is attributed to unsuccessful economic liberalisation programmes spearheaded by foreign companies and governments, but other studies have cited bad domestic government policies more than external factors.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Africa is now at risk of being in debt once again, particularly in sub-Saharan African countries.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The last debt crisis in 2005 was resolved with help from the heavily indebted poor countries scheme (HIPC).
[src:banana/africa-p02] The HIPC resulted in some positive and negative effects on the economy in Africa.
[src:banana/africa-p02] About ten years after the 2005 debt crisis in sub-Saharan Africa was resolved, Zambia fell back into debt.
[src:banana/africa-p02] A small reason was due to the fall in copper prices in 2011, but the bigger reason was that a large amount of the money Zambia borrowed was wasted or pocketed by the elite.
[src:banana/africa-p02] From 1995 to 2005, Africa's rate of economic growth increased, averaging 5% in 2005.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Some countries experienced still higher growth rates, notably Angola, Sudan and Equatorial Guinea, all of which had recently begun extracting their petroleum reserves or had expanded their oil extraction capacity.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The following table shows the projected nominal GDP and GDP per capita (at purchasing power parity) in 2026 by the IMF.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The continent is believed to hold 90% of the world's cobalt, 90% of its platinum, 50% of its gold, 98% of its chromium, 70% of its tantalite, 64% of its manganese and one-third of its uranium.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) has 70% of the world's coltan, a mineral used in the production of tantalum capacitors for electronic devices such as cell phones.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The DRC also has more than 30% of the world's diamond reserves.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Guinea is the world's largest exporter of bauxite.
[src:banana/africa-p02] As the growth in Africa has been driven mainly by services and not manufacturing or agriculture, it has been growth without jobs and without reduction in poverty levels.
[src:banana/africa-p02] In fact, the food security crisis of 2008, which took place following the global financial crisis, pushed 100 million people into food insecurity.
[src:banana/africa-p02] In 2024 nearly 307 million people in Africa were undernourished (46% of the global total), an increase of 10 million people since 2023 and 34 million from 2022.
[src:banana/africa-p02] In recent years, China has built increasingly stronger ties with African nations and is Africa's largest trading partner.
[src:banana/africa-p02] In 2007, Chinese companies invested a total of US$1 billion in Africa.
[src:banana/africa-p02] A Harvard University study led by professor Calestous Juma showed that Africa could feed itself by making the transition from importer to self-sufficiency.
[src:banana/africa-p02] "African agriculture is at the crossroads; we have come to the end of a century of policies that favoured Africa's export of raw materials and importation of food.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Cooking with biogas in Tanzania; Geothermal energy infrastructure in Kenya; Coal power station in South Africa; Solar-powered lamp-light in Zambia.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Energy in Africa is characterised by low per-capita consumption and limited access to modern energy services, reflecting both infrastructural and socio-economic challenges across the continent.
[src:banana/africa-p02] As of 2023, Africa accounted for just 5.5% of global total final energy consumption, with per-capita energy use more than three times lower than the global average.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The energy mix is dominated by biofuels and waste, which make up 43% of total final consumption, primarily for household cooking and heating, followed by oil products at 33%, electricity at 11%, natural gas at 9%, and coal at 4%.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Electricity access remains a major challenge, particularly in Sub-Saharan Africa, where nearly 450 million rural residents lack reliable electricity, and grid coverage is often inconsistent.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Clean cooking solutions are similarly underdeveloped, leaving over 900 million people reliant on polluting fuels such as firewood, charcoal, and agricultural residues, which disproportionately affect women and children.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Transport energy is dominated by oil products, reflecting low motorisation rates and limited adoption of electric mobility, although countries such as Ethiopia, Morocco, and Egypt have begun adopting policies to reduce fossil fuel dependency.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Africa possesses some of the world's most abundant energy resources, including oil, natural gas, coal, hydropower, solar, wind, geothermal, and biomass, much of which remains underutilised.
[src:banana/africa-p02] While fossil fuels such as coal, oil, and natural gas continue to dominate energy production and electricity generation in Africa, renewable sources are increasingly expanding across the continent.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Hydropower, solar, wind, geothermal, and modern biomass are growing in capacity, though their deployment remains uneven and limited compared to the continent's vast potential.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Hydropower is the largest non-combustible renewable source, while solar energy offers immense potential due to high irradiation levels, particularly in the Sahara and Sahel.
[src:banana/africa-p02] There are regional differences: North Africa is dominated by oil and gas production, Southern Africa by coal and hydropower, East Africa by hydropower and geothermal, and West and Central Africa face major electrification gaps despite hydroelectric potential.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Water development and management are complex in Africa due to the multiplicity of trans-boundary water resources (rivers, lakes and aquifers).
[src:banana/africa-p02] Around 75% of sub-Saharan Africa falls within 53 international river basin catchments that traverse multiple borders.
[src:banana/africa-p02] This particular constraint can also be converted into an opportunity if the potential for trans-boundary cooperation is harnessed in the development of the area's water resources.
[src:banana/africa-p02] A multi-sectoral analysis of the Zambezi River, for example, shows that riparian cooperation could lead to a 23% increase in firm energy production without any additional investments.
[src:banana/africa-p02] A number of institutional and legal frameworks for transboundary cooperation exist, such as the Zambezi River Authority, the Southern African Development Community (SADC) Protocol, Volta River Authority and the Nile Basin Commission.
[src:banana/africa-p02] However, additional efforts are required to further develop political will, as well as the financial capacities and institutional frameworks needed for win-win multilateral cooperative actions and optimal solutions for all riparians.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Africa is considered by anthropologists to be the most genetically diverse continent as a result of being the longest inhabited.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Africa's population has rapidly increased over the last 40 years, and is consequently relatively young.
[src:banana/africa-p02] In some African states, more than half the population is under 25 years of age.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The total number of people in Africa increased from 229 million in 1950 to 630 million in 1990.
[src:banana/africa-p02] As of 2021, the population of Africa is estimated at 1,394 million.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Africa's total population surpassing other continents is fairly recent; African population surpassed Europe in the 1990s, while the Americas was overtaken sometime around the year 2000.
[src:banana/africa-p02] This increase in number of babies born in Africa compared to the rest of the world is expected to reach approximately 37% in the year 2050; while in 1990 sub-Saharan Africa accounted for only 16% of the world's births.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The total fertility rate (children per woman) for Sub-Saharan Africa is 4.7 as of 2018, the highest in the world.
[src:banana/africa-p02] All countries in sub-Saharan Africa had TFRs (average number of children) above replacement level in 2019 and accounted for 27.1% of global livebirths.
[src:banana/africa-p02] In 2021, sub-Saharan Africa accounted for 29% of global births.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Speakers of Bantu languages (part of the Niger–Congo family) are the majority in southern, central and southeast Africa.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The Bantu-speaking peoples from the Sahel progressively expanded over most of sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:banana/africa-p02] But there are also several Nilotic groups in South Sudan and East Africa, the mixed Swahili people on the Swahili Coast, and a few remaining indigenous Khoisan ("San" or "Bushmen") and Pygmy peoples in Southern and Central Africa, respectively.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Bantu-speaking Africans also predominate in Gabon and Equatorial Guinea, and are found in parts of southern Cameroon.
[src:banana/africa-p02] In the Kalahari Desert of Southern Africa, the distinct people known as the Bushmen (also "San", closely related to, but distinct from "Hottentots") have long been present.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The San are physically distinct from other Africans and are the indigenous people of southern Africa.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Pygmies are the pre-Bantu indigenous peoples of central Africa.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The peoples of West Africa primarily speak Niger–Congo languages, belonging mostly to its non-Bantu branches, though some Nilo-Saharan and Afro-Asiatic speaking groups are also found.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The Niger–Congo-speaking Yoruba, Igbo, Fulani, Akan, and Wolof ethnic groups are the largest and most influential.
[src:banana/africa-p02] In the central Sahara, Mandinka or Mande groups are most significant.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Chadic-speaking groups, including the Hausa, are found in more northerly parts of the region nearest to the Sahara, and Nilo-Saharan communities, such as the Songhai, Kanuri, and Zarma, are found in the eastern parts of West Africa bordering Central Africa.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The peoples of North Africa consist of three main indigenous groups: Berbers in the northwest, Egyptians in the northeast, and Nilo-Saharan-speaking peoples in the east.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The Arabs who arrived in the 7th century AD introduced the Arabic language and Islam to North Africa.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The Semitic Phoenicians (who founded Carthage) and Hyksos, the Indo-Iranian Alans, the Indo-European Greeks, Romans, and Vandals settled in North Africa as well.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Significant Berber communities remain within Morocco and Algeria in the 21st century, while, to a lesser extent, Berber speakers are also present in some regions of Tunisia and Libya.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The Berber-speaking Tuareg and other often-nomadic peoples are the principal inhabitants of the Saharan interior of North Africa.
[src:banana/africa-p02] In Mauritania, there is a small but near-extinct Berber community in the north and Niger–Congo-speaking peoples in the south, though in both regions Arabic and Arab culture predominates.
[src:banana/africa-p02] In Sudan, although Arabic and Arab culture predominate, it is mostly inhabited by groups that originally spoke Nilo-Saharan, such as the Nubians, Fur, Masalit and Zaghawa, who, over the centuries, have variously intermixed with migrants from the Arabian peninsula.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Small communities of Afro-Asiatic-speaking Beja nomads can also be found in Egypt and Sudan.
[src:banana/africa-p02] In the Horn of Africa, some Ethiopian and Eritrean groups (like the Amhara and Tigrayans, collectively known as Habesha) speak languages from the Semitic branch of the Afro-Asiatic language family, while the Oromo and Somali speak languages from the Cushitic branch of Afro-Asiatic.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Prior to the decolonisation movements of the post-World War II era, Europeans were represented in every part of Africa.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Decolonization during the 1960s and 1970s often resulted in the mass emigration of white settlers—especially from Algeria and Morocco (1.6 million *pieds-noirs* in North Africa), Kenya, Congo, Rhodesia, Mozambique and Angola.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Between 1975 and 1977, over a million colonials returned to Portugal alone.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Nevertheless, white Africans remain an important minority in many African states, particularly Zimbabwe, Namibia, Réunion, and South Africa.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The country with the largest white African population is South Africa.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Dutch and British diasporas represent the largest communities of European ancestry on the continent today.
[src:banana/africa-p02] European colonisation also brought sizable groups of Asians, particularly from the Indian subcontinent, to British colonies.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Large Indian communities are found in South Africa, and smaller ones are present in Kenya, Tanzania, and some other southern and southeast African countries.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The large Indian community in Uganda was expelled by the dictator Idi Amin in 1972, though many have since returned.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The islands in the Indian Ocean are also populated primarily by people of Asian origin, often mixed with Africans and Europeans.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The Malagasy people of Madagascar are an Austronesian people, but those along the coast are generally mixed with Bantu, Arab, Indian and European origins.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Malay and Indian ancestries are also important components in the group of people known in South Africa as Cape Coloureds (people with origins in two or more races and continents).
[src:banana/africa-p02] During the 20th century, small but economically important communities of Lebanese have also developed in the larger coastal cities of West and East Africa, respectively.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The Sahara served as a trans-regional passageway and place of dwelling for people in Africa during various humid phases and periods throughout the history of Africa.
[src:banana/africa-p02] As early as 11,000 years ago, Sub-Saharan West Africans, bearing macrohaplogroup L (e.g., L1b1a11, L1b1a6a, L1b1a8, L1b1a9a1, L2a1k, L3d1b1a), may have migrated through North Africa and into Europe, mostly into southern Europe (e.g., Iberia).
[src:banana/africa-p02] The genetic marker E1b1 was identified to have wide distribution across Egypt, with "P2/215/M35.1 (E1b1b), for short M35, likely also originated in eastern tropical Africa, and is predominantly distributed in an arc from the Horn of Africa up through Egypt".
[src:banana/africa-p02] The R haplogroup has also been identified to have high frequencies in central Saharan Africa, among some Afro-Asiatic and Nilo-Saharan language speaking groups.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Genetic evidence has identified the Horn of Africa to be the source of a genetic marker "M35/215" Y-chromosome lineage for a significant population component which moved north from that region into Egypt and the Levant.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Historian Christopher Ehret argued that this genetic distribution paralleled the spread of the Afrasian language family with the movement of people from the Horn of Africa into Egypt and added a new demic component to the existing population of Egypt 17,000 years ago.
[src:banana/africa-p02] According to a recent study, the Arab migrations to the Maghreb was mainly a demographic process that heavily implied gene flow and remodelled the genetic structure of the Maghreb region in North Africa, rather than a mere cultural replacement as claimed by older studies.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Another study found out that the majority of J-M267 (Eu10) chromosomes in the Maghreb are due to the recent gene flow caused by the Arab migrations to the Maghreb in the first millennium CE as both southern Qahtanite and northern Adnanite Arabs added to the heterogenous Maghrebi ethnic melting pot.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The Eu10 chromosome pool in the Maghreb is derived not only from early Neolithic dispersions from Western Asia but to a much greater extent from recent expansions of Arab tribes from the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:banana/africa-p02] David Schoenbrun, Christopher Ehret, Steven A.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Brandt and Shomarka Keita (2025) have highlighted the problematic categorisation of genetic haplogroups characterised as ‘African’ and ‘Eurasian' in North African genome studies.
[src:banana/africa-p02] In reference to the van de Loosdrecht et al.
[src:banana/africa-p02] In their view, identifying a range of African populations may still remain an issue “since the idea of ‘African’ still gets stereotyped or restricted.
[src:banana/africa-p02] (Accepting the southwestern Asian/Levantine geographical continuity with Africa eliminates a conceptual barrier related to racio-typological thinking permitting an Africasian construct analogous to Eurasian.)”.
[src:banana/africa-p02] While Africans profess a wide variety of religious beliefs, the majority of the people respect African religions or parts of them.
[src:banana/africa-p02] However, in formal surveys or census, most people will identify with major religions that came from outside the continent, mainly through colonisation.
[src:banana/africa-p02] There are several reasons for this, the main one being the colonial idea that African religious beliefs and practices are not good enough.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Religious beliefs and statistics on religious affiliation are difficult to come by since they are often a sensitive topic for governments with mixed religious populations.
[src:banana/africa-p02] According to the *World Book Encyclopedia*, Islam and Christianity are the two largest religions in Africa.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Islam is most prevalent in Northern Africa, and is the state religion of many North African countries, such as Algeria, where 99% of the population practices Islam.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The majority of people in most governments in Southern, Southeast, and Central Africa, as well as in a sizable portion of the Horn of Africa and West Africa, identify as Christians.
[src:banana/africa-p02] The Coptic Christians constitute a sizable minority in Egypt, and the Ethiopian Orthodox Church is the largest church in Ethiopia, with 36 million and 51 million adherents.
[src:banana/africa-p02] According to Encyclopædia Britannica, 45% of the population are Christians, 40% are Muslims, and 10% follow traditional religions.
[src:banana/africa-p02] A small number of Africans are Hindu, Buddhist, Confucianist, Baháʼí, or Jewish.
[src:banana/africa-p02] There is also a minority of people in Africa who are irreligious.
[src:banana/africa-p02] By most estimates, well over a thousand languages (UNESCO has estimated around two thousand) are spoken in Africa.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Most are of African origin, though some are of European or Asian origin.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Africa is the most multilingual continent in the world, and it is not rare for individuals to fluently speak not only multiple African languages, but one or more European ones as well.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Following the end of colonialism, nearly all African countries adopted official languages that originated outside the continent, although several countries also granted legal recognition to indigenous languages (such as Swahili, Yoruba, Igbo and Hausa).
[src:banana/africa-p02] In numerous countries, English and French (*see African French*) are used for communication in the public sphere such as government, commerce, education and the media.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Arabic, Portuguese, Afrikaans and Spanish are examples of languages that trace their origin to outside of Africa, and that are used by millions of Africans today, both in the public and private spheres.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Italian is spoken by some in former Italian colonies in Africa.
[src:banana/africa-p02] German is spoken in Namibia, as it was a former German protectorate.
[src:banana/africa-p02] In total, at least a fifth of Africans speak the former colonial languages.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Moreover, in recent years some African countries have been considering removing their official former colonial languages, such as Mali, Burkina Faso and Niger which removed French as an official language in the 2020s in favour of native languages, while also renaming colonial street names.
[src:banana/africa-p02] More than 85% of individuals in Africa use traditional medicine as an alternative to often expensive allopathic medical health care and costly pharmaceutical products.
[src:banana/africa-p02] AIDS in post-colonial Africa is a prevalent issue.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Although the continent is home to about 15.2 percent of the world's population, more than two-thirds of the total infected worldwide—some 35 million people—were Africans, of whom 15 million have already died.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Sub-Saharan Africa alone accounted for an estimated 69 percent of all people living with HIV and 70 percent of all AIDS deaths in 2011.
[src:banana/africa-p02] In the countries of sub-Saharan Africa most affected, AIDS has raised death rates and lowered life expectancy among adults between the ages of 20 and 49 by about twenty years.
[src:banana/africa-p02] Furthermore, the life expectancy in many parts of Africa has declined, largely as a result of the HIV/AIDS epidemic with life-expectancy in some countries reaching as low as thirty-four years.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Africa is divided into a great number of ethnic cultures.
[src:banana/africa-p03] In recent times, the call for a much greater emphasis on the cultural dimension in all aspects of development has become increasingly vocal.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Some aspects of traditional African cultures have become less practised in recent years as a result of neglect and suppression by colonial and post-colonial regimes.
[src:banana/africa-p03] For example, African customs were discouraged, and African languages were prohibited in mission schools, while colonialists such as Leopold II of Belgium attempted to "civilize" Africans by discouraging polygamy and witchcraft.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Abiola Irele and Simon Gikandi comment that the current identity of African literature had its genesis in the "traumatic encounter between Africa and Europe".
[src:banana/africa-p03] On the other hand, Mhoze Chikowero believes that Africans deployed music, dance, spirituality, and other performative cultures to (re)assert themselves as active agents and indigenous intellectuals, to unmake their colonial marginalisation and reshape their own destinies.
[src:banana/africa-p03] As of March 2023, 98 African properties are listed by UNESCO as World Heritage Sites.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Among these proprieties, 54 are cultural sites, 39 are natural sites and 5 are mixed sites.
[src:banana/africa-p03] The List of World Heritage in Danger includes 15 African sites.
[src:banana/africa-p03] African art refers to works of visual art, including works of sculpture, painting, metalwork, and pottery, originating from the various peoples of the African continent and influenced by distinct, indigenous traditions of aesthetic expression.
[src:banana/africa-p03] While the various artistic traditions of such a large and diverse continent display considerable regional and cultural variety, there are consistent artistic themes, recurring motifs, and unifying elements across the broad spectrum of the African visual expression.
[src:banana/africa-p03] As is the case for every artistic tradition in human history, African art was created within specific social, political, and religious contexts.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Likewise, African art was often created not purely for art's sake, but rather with some practical, spiritual, and/or didactic purpose in mind.
[src:banana/africa-p03] In general, African art prioritizes conceptual and symbolic representation over realism, aiming to visualize the subject's spiritual essence.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Ethiopian art, heavily influenced by Ethiopia's long-standing Christian tradition, is also different from most African art, where Traditional African religion (with Islam prevalent in the north east and north west presently) was dominant until the 20th century.
[src:banana/africa-p03] African art includes prehistoric and ancient art, the Islamic art of West Africa, the Christian art of East Africa, and the traditional artifacts of these and other regions.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Many African sculptures were historically made of wood and other natural materials that have not survived from earlier than a few centuries ago, although rare older pottery and metal figures can be found in some areas.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Some of the earliest decorative objects, such as shell beads and evidence of paint, have been discovered in Africa, dating to the Middle Stone Age.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Masks are important elements in the art of many people, along with human figures, and are often highly stylized.
[src:banana/africa-p03] There exist diverse styles, which can often be observed within a single context of origin and may be influenced by the intended use of the object.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Nevertheless, broad regional trends are discernible.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Sculpture is most common among "groups of settled cultivators in the areas drained by the Niger and Congo rivers" in West Africa.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Direct images of deities are relatively infrequent, but masks in particular are or were often made for ritual ceremonies.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Since the late 19th century, there has been an increasing amount of African art in Western collections, the finest pieces of which are displayed as part of the history of colonization.
[src:banana/africa-p03] African art had an important influence on European Modernist art, which was inspired by their interest in abstract depiction.
[src:banana/africa-p03] It was this appreciation of African sculpture that has been attributed to the very concept of "African art", as seen by European and American artists and art historians.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Obidoh Freeborn posits that colonialism is one element that has created the character of modern African art.
[src:banana/africa-p03] According to authors Douglas Fraser and Herbert M.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Author Chika Okeke-Agulu states that "the racist infrastructure of British imperial enterprise forced upon the political and cultural guardians of empire a denial and suppression of an emergent sovereign Africa and modernist art".
[src:banana/africa-p03] scaling: small parts of the structure tend to look similar to larger parts, such as a circular village made of circular houses.
[src:banana/africa-p03] African architecture in some areas has been influenced by external cultures for centuries, according to available evidence.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Western architecture has influenced coastal areas since the late 15th century and is now an important source of inspiration for many larger buildings, particularly in major cities.
[src:banana/africa-p03] African architecture uses a wide range of materials, including thatch, stick/wood, mud, mudbrick, rammed earth, and stone.
[src:banana/africa-p03] These material preferences vary by region: North Africa for stone and rammed earth, the Horn of Africa for stone and mortar, West Africa for mud/adobe, Central Africa for thatch/wood and more perishable materials, Southeast and Southern Africa for stone and thatch/wood.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Cinema of Africa refers to the film industries and films produced in the continent of Africa.
[src:banana/africa-p03] It covers both the history and present of the making or screening of films on the African continent, and also refers to the persons involved in this form of audiovisual culture.
[src:banana/africa-p03] It dates back to the late 19th century, when film reels were the primary cinematic technology in use.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Cairo has been the capital of film industry in Africa since the early 20th century to the present day.
[src:banana/africa-p03] As there are more than 50 countries with audiovisual traditions, there is no one single 'African cinema'.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Both historically and culturally, there are major regional differences between North African and sub-Saharan cinemas, and between the cinemas of different countries.
[src:banana/africa-p03] The Egyptian film industry and the Tunisian are also among the oldest in the world.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Cinema of Egypt in particular is the most established and flourishing industry in Africa.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Pioneers Auguste and Louis Lumière screened their films in Alexandria, Cairo, Tunis, Susa, Libya and Hammam-Lif, Tunisia in 1896.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Albert Samama Chikly is often cited as the first producer of indigenous African cinema, screening his own short documentaries in the casino of Tunis as early as December 1905.
[src:banana/africa-p03] The continent of Africa and its music is vast and highly diverse, with different regions and nations maintaining distinct musical traditions.
[src:banana/africa-p03] African music includes genres such as makwaya, highlife, mbube, township music, jùjú, fuji, jaiva, afrobeat, afrofusion, mbalax, Congolese rumba, soukous, ndombolo, makossa, kizomba, and taarab, among others.
[src:banana/africa-p03] African music also uses a wide variety of instruments from across the continent.
[src:banana/africa-p03] The music and dance traditions of the African diaspora, shaped to varying degrees by African musical traditions, include American genres such as Dixieland jazz, blues, and jazz, as well as Caribbean styles such as calypso (see kaiso), and soca.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Latin American music genres including cumbia, salsa, son cubano, rumba, conga, bomba, samba, and zouk developed from the music of enslaved Africans and have, in turn, influenced contemporary African popular music.
[src:banana/africa-p03] African dance (also Afro dance, Afrodance and Afro-dance) refers to the various dance styles of sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:banana/africa-p03] These dances are closely connected with the traditional rhythms and music traditions of the region.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Music and dancing is an integral part of many traditional African societies.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Songs and dances facilitate teaching and promoting social values, the celebration of special events and major life milestones, the performance of oral history and other recitations, and spiritual experiences.
[src:banana/africa-p03] African dance uses the concepts of polyrhythm and total body articulation.
[src:banana/africa-p03] African dances are often a collective activity performed in large groups, with significant interaction between dancers and onlookers.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Fifty-four African countries have football teams in the Confederation of African Football.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Egypt has won the African Cup seven times, and a record-making three times in a row.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Cameroon, Nigeria, Morocco, Senegal, Ghana, and Algeria have advanced to the knockout stage of recent FIFA World Cups.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Morocco, at the 2022 World Cup in Qatar was the first African nation to reach the semi-finals of the FIFA Men's World Cup.
[src:banana/africa-p03] South Africa hosted the 2010 World Cup tournament, becoming the first African country to do so.
[src:banana/africa-p03] The top clubs in each African football league play the CAF Champions League, while lower-ranked clubs compete in CAF Confederation Cup.
[src:banana/africa-p03] In recent years, the continent has progressed in terms of state-of-the-art basketball facilities, which have been built in cities such as Cairo, Dakar, Johannesburg, Kigali, Luanda, and Rades.
[src:banana/africa-p03] The number of African basketball players who drafted into the U.S.
[src:banana/africa-p03] NBA has experienced growth in the 2010s.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Cricket is popular in some African nations.
[src:banana/africa-p03] South Africa and Zimbabwe have Test status, while Kenya is the leading non-test team and previously had One-Day International cricket (ODI) status (from 10 October 1997, until 30 January 2014).
[src:banana/africa-p03] The three countries jointly hosted the 2003 Cricket World Cup.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Namibia is the other African country to have played in a World Cup.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Morocco, in northern Africa, hosted the 2002 Morocco Cup, but the national team has never qualified for a major tournament.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Rugby is popular in several southern African nations.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Namibia and Zimbabwe have appeared on multiple occasions at the Rugby World Cup, while South Africa is the most successful national team at the Rugby World Cup, having won the tournament on four occasions, in 1995, 2007, 2019, and 2023.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Traditional sports were strictly marginalised during the colonial era, and many are dying or have gone extinct under the pressure of modernisation, however lots remain popular despite not having formal governmental recognition or support.
[src:banana/africa-p03] Some examples are Senegalese wrestling, Dambe, Nguni stick-fighting, and Savika.
[src:banana/apg-iii-system] The **APG III system** of flowering plant classification is the third version of a modern, mostly molecular-based, system of plant taxonomy being developed by the Angiosperm Phylogeny Group (APG).
[src:banana/apg-iii-system] Published in 2009, it was superseded in 2016 by a further revision, the APG IV system.
[src:banana/apg-iii-system] The APG III system recognized all of the 45 orders of the previous system, as well as 14 new ones.
[src:banana/apg-iii-system] The order Ceratophyllales was erroneously marked as a new order, as it had been recognized in both of the previous APG systems.
[src:banana/apg-iii-system] The designation of alternative "bracketed families" was abandoned in APG III, because its inclusion in the previous system had been unpopular.
[src:banana/apg-iii-system] APG III recognized 413 families, 43 fewer than in the previous system.
[src:banana/apg-iii-system] Forty-four of the 55 "bracketed families" were discontinued, and 20 other families were discontinued as well.
[src:banana/apg-iii-system] 21 families were accepted in the APG III system which had not been in the previous system, and a few families were moved to a different position.
[src:banana/apg-iii-system] The number of families not placed in any order was reduced from 39 to 10.
[src:banana/apg-iii-system] Apodanthaceae and Cynomoriaceae were placed among the angiosperms, incertae sedis, that is, not in any group within the angiosperms.
[src:banana/apg-iii-system] Eight other families were placed incertae sedis in various supra-ordinal groups within the angiosperms.
[src:banana/apg-iii-system] The paragraph below shows the number of families in each order and the placement of those families that were not included in any order.
[src:banana/apg-iii-system] These figures were produced by simply counting the families in the text of the paper that established APG III.
[src:banana/apg-iii-system] SUPRA-ORDINAL GROUPS: commelinids (1), basal eudicots (1), Pentapetalae (1), lamiids incertae sedis (3), core lamiids (2), angiosperms incertae sedis (2).
[src:banana/apg-iii-system] The circumscription of the family Icacinaceae remains especially doubtful.
[src:banana/apg-iii-system] *Apodytes* and its close relative, Rhaphiostylis, as well as *Emmotum*, *Cassinopsis*, and a few other genera were provisionally retained within it until further studies can determine whether they properly belong there.
[src:banana/apg-iii-system] Three genera (*Gumillea*, *Nicobariodendron*, and *Petenaea*) were placed within the angiosperms incertae sedis.
[src:banana/apg-iii-system] *Nicobariodendron* and *Petenaea* were newly added to the list.
[src:banana/apg-iii-system] The classification is shown below in two versions.
[src:banana/apg-iii-system] The short version goes to the level of orders and of families unplaced in an order.
[src:banana/apg-iii-system] The detailed version shows all the families.
[src:banana/apg-iii-system] Orders at the same level in the classification are arranged alphabetically.
[src:banana/apg-iii-system] Note that orders may not contain the same families as in earlier versions of the APG system (APG system, APG II system).
[src:banana/apg-iii-system] Further detail on relationships can be seen in the phylogenetic tree below.
[src:banana/apg-iii-system] The APG III system was based on a phylogenetic tree for the angiosperms which included all of the 59 orders and 4 of the unplaced families.
[src:banana/apg-iii-system] The systematic positions of the other 6 unplaced families was so uncertain that they could not be placed in any of the polytomies in the tree.
[src:banana/apg-iii-system] They are shown in the classification table entitled "Detailed version" above, 4 in Euasterids I and 2 in Taxa of uncertain position.
[src:banana/apg-iii-system] The phylogenetic tree shown below was published with the APG III system, but without some of the labels that are added here.
[src:banana/apg-iii-system] A number of subfamilies have been proposed to replace some of the families which were optional (i.e. bracketed) in APG II, but have been discontinued in APG III.
[src:banana/banana-p01] A **banana** is an elongated, edible fruit that is botanically a berry produced by several kinds of large treelike herbaceous flowering plants in the genus *Musa*.
[src:banana/banana-p01] In some countries, cooking bananas are called plantains, distinguishing them from **dessert bananas**.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The fruit is variable in size, color and firmness, but is usually elongated and curved, with soft flesh rich in starch covered with a peel, which may have a variety of colors when ripe.
[src:banana/banana-p01] It grows upward in clusters near the top of the plant.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Almost all modern edible seedless (parthenocarp) cultivated bananas come from two wild species – *Musa acuminata* and *Musa balbisiana*, or their hybrids.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Worldwide, there is no sharp distinction between dessert "bananas" and cooking "plantains": this distinction works well enough in the Americas and Europe, but it breaks down in Southeast Asia where many more kinds of bananas are grown and eaten.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The term "banana" is applied also to other members of the *Musa* genus, such as the scarlet banana (*Musa coccinea*), the pink banana (*Musa velutina*), and the Fe'i bananas.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Members of the genus *Ensete*, such as the snow banana (*Ensete glaucum*) and the economically important false banana (*Ensete ventricosum*) of Africa are sometimes included.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Both genera are in the banana family, Musaceae.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Banana plantations can be damaged by parasitic nematodes and insect pests, and to fungal and bacterial diseases, one of the most serious being Panama disease which is caused by a *Fusarium* fungus.
[src:banana/banana-p01] This and black sigatoka threaten the production of Cavendish bananas, the main kind eaten in the Western world, which is a triploid *Musa acuminata*.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Plant breeders are seeking new varieties, but these are difficult to breed given that commercial varieties are seedless.
[src:banana/banana-p01] To enable future breeding, banana germplasm is conserved in multiple gene banks around the world.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The banana plant is the largest herbaceous flowering plant.
[src:banana/banana-p01] All the above-ground parts of a banana plant grow from a structure called a corm.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Plants are normally tall and fairly sturdy with a tree-like appearance, but what appears to be a trunk is actually a pseudostem composed of multiple leaf-stalks (petioles).
[src:banana/banana-p01] Bananas grow in a wide variety of soils, as long as it is at least 60 centimetres (2.0 ft) deep, has good drainage and is not compacted.
[src:banana/banana-p01] They are fast-growing plants, with a growth rate of up to 1.6 metres (5.2 ft) per day.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The leaves of banana plants are composed of a stalk (petiole) and a blade (lamina).
[src:banana/banana-p01] The base of the petiole widens to form a sheath; the tightly packed sheaths make up the pseudostem, which is all that supports the plant.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The edges of the sheath meet when it is first produced, making it tubular.
[src:banana/banana-p01] As new growth occurs in the centre of the pseudostem, the edges are forced apart.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Cultivated banana plants vary in height depending on the variety and growing conditions.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Most are around 5 m (16 ft) tall, with a range from 'Dwarf Cavendish' plants at around 3 m (9.8 ft) to 'Gros Michel' at 7 m (23 ft) or more.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Leaves are spirally arranged and may grow 2.7 metres (8.9 ft) long and 60 cm (2.0 ft) wide.
[src:banana/banana-p01] When a banana plant is mature, the corm stops producing new leaves and begins to form a flower spike or inflorescence.
[src:banana/banana-p01] A stem develops which grows up inside the pseudostem, carrying the immature inflorescence until eventually it emerges at the top.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Each pseudostem normally produces a single inflorescence, also known as the "banana heart".
[src:banana/banana-p01] After fruiting, the pseudostem dies, but offshoots will normally have developed from the base, so that the plant as a whole is perennial.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The inflorescence contains many petal-like bracts between rows of flowers.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The female flowers (which can develop into fruit) appear in rows further up the stem (closer to the leaves) from the rows of male flowers.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The ovary is inferior, meaning that the tiny petals and other flower parts appear at the tip of the ovary.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The banana fruits develop from the *banana heart*, in a large hanging cluster called a *bunch*, made up of around nine tiers called *hands*, with up to 20 fruits to a hand.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The stalk ends of the fruits connect up to the rachis part of the inflorescence.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Opposite the stalk end, is the blossom end, where the remnants of the flower deviate the texture from the rest of the flesh inside the peel.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The fruit has been described as a "leathery berry".
[src:banana/banana-p01] There is a protective outer layer (a peel or skin) with numerous long, thin strings (Vascular bundles), which run lengthwise between the skin and the edible inner white flesh.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The peel is less palatable and usually discarded after peeling the fruit.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The inner part of the common yellow dessert variety can be split lengthwise into three sections that correspond to the inner portions of the three carpels by manually deforming the unopened fruit.
[src:banana/banana-p01] In cultivated varieties, fertile seeds are usually absent.
[src:banana/banana-p01] A 2011 phylogenomic analysis using nuclear genes indicates the phylogeny of some representatives of the Musaceae family.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Major edible kinds of banana are shown in **boldface**.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Work by Li and colleagues in 2024 identifies three subspecies of *M. acuminata*, namely sspp.
[src:banana/banana-p01] *banksii*, *malaccensis*, and *zebrina*, as contributing substantially to the *Ban*, *Dh*, and *Ze* subgenomes of triploid cultivated bananas respectively.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The genus *Musa* was created by Carl Linnaeus in 1753.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The name may be derived from Antonius Musa, physician to the Emperor Augustus, or Linnaeus may have adapted the Arabic word for banana, *mauz*.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The word "banana" is thought to be of West African origin, possibly from the Wolof word *banaana*, and passed into English via Spanish or Portuguese.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The classification of cultivated bananas has long been a problematic issue for taxonomists.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Linnaeus originally placed bananas into two species based only on their uses as food: *Musa sapientum* for dessert bananas and *Musa paradisiaca* for plantains.
[src:banana/banana-p01] More species names were added, but this approach proved to be inadequate for the number of cultivars in the primary center of diversity of the genus, Southeast Asia.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Many of these cultivars were given names that were later discovered to be synonyms.
[src:banana/banana-p01] In a series of papers published from 1947 onward, Ernest Cheesman showed that Linnaeus's *Musa sapientum* and *Musa paradisiaca* were cultivars and descendants of two wild seed-producing species, *Musa acuminata* and *Musa balbisiana*, both first described by Luigi Aloysius Colla.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Researchers Norman Simmonds and Ken Shepherd proposed a genome-based nomenclature system in 1955.
[src:banana/banana-p01] This system eliminated almost all the difficulties and inconsistencies of the earlier classification of bananas based on assigning scientific names to cultivated varieties.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Despite this, the original names are still recognized by some authorities, leading to confusion.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The accepted scientific names for most groups of cultivated bananas are *Musa acuminata* Colla and *Musa balbisiana* Colla for the ancestral species, and *Musa* × *paradisiaca* L. for the hybrid of the two.
[src:banana/banana-p01] An unusual feature of the genetics of the banana is that chloroplast DNA is inherited maternally, while mitochondrial DNA is inherited paternally.
[src:banana/banana-p01] This facilitates taxonomic study of species and subspecies relationships.
[src:banana/banana-p01] In regions such as North America and Europe, *Musa* fruits offered for sale can be divided into small sweet "bananas" eaten raw when ripe as a dessert, and large starchy "plantains" or cooking bananas, which do not have to be ripe.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Linnaeus made this distinction when naming two "species" of *Musa*.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Members of the "plantain subgroup" of banana cultivars, most important as food in West Africa and Latin America, correspond to this description, having long pointed fruit.
[src:banana/banana-p01] They are described by Ploetz et al. as "true" plantains, distinct from other cooking bananas.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The cooking bananas of East Africa belong to a different group, the East African Highland bananas.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Further, small farmers in Colombia grow a much wider range of cultivars than large commercial plantations do, and in Southeast Asia—the center of diversity for bananas, both wild and cultivated—the distinction between "bananas" and "plantains" does not work.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Many bananas are used both raw and cooked.
[src:banana/banana-p01] There are starchy cooking bananas which are smaller than those eaten raw.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The range of colors, sizes and shapes is far wider than in those grown or sold in Africa, Europe or the Americas.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Southeast Asian languages do not make the distinction between "bananas" and "plantains" that is made in English.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Thus both Cavendish dessert bananas and Saba cooking bananas are called *pisang* in Malaysia and Indonesia, *kluai* in Thailand and *chuối* in Vietnam.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Fe'i bananas, grown and eaten in the islands of the Pacific, are derived from a different wild species.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Most Fe'i bananas are cooked, but Karat bananas, which are short and squat with bright red skins, are eaten raw.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The earliest domestication of bananas (*Musa* spp.) was from naturally occurring parthenocarpic (seedless) individuals of *Musa banksii* in New Guinea.
[src:banana/banana-p01] These were cultivated by Papuans before the arrival of Austronesian-speakers.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Numerous phytoliths of bananas have been recovered from the Kuk Swamp archaeological site and dated to around 10,000 to 6,500 BP.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Foraging humans in this area began domestication in the late Pleistocene using transplantation and early cultivation methods.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Various investigations – including Denham *et al.*, 2003 – determine that by the early to middle of the Holocene the process was complete.
[src:banana/banana-p01] From New Guinea, cultivated bananas spread westward into Island Southeast Asia.
[src:banana/banana-p01] They hybridized with other (possibly independently domesticated) subspecies of *Musa acuminata* as well as *M. balbisiana* in the Philippines, northern New Guinea, and possibly Halmahera.
[src:banana/banana-p01] These hybridization events produced the triploid cultivars of bananas commonly grown today.
[src:banana/banana-p01] From Island Southeast Asia, they became part of the staple domesticated crops of the Austronesian peoples and were spread via their ancient seaborne migrations and ancient maritime trading routes into Oceania, Africa, South Asia, and Indochina.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Bananas are believed to have been introduced to Africa from Southeast Asia via the Austronesian settlement of Madagascar (c.
[src:banana/banana-p01] However, the role of Madagascar as a staging board for the dispersal of bananas (and other Asian crops) is unclear.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Malagasy people colonized Madagascar from Island Southeast Asia around 600 AD onwards, but contact between East Africa and Island Southeast Asia dates back to at least 300 BC or earlier.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The possibility that bananas may have been introduced from earlier Austronesian settlements in the East African coast that pre-date the settlement of Madagascar can not be ruled out.
[src:banana/banana-p01] These ancient introductions resulted in the banana subgroup now known as the "true" plantains, which include the East African Highland bananas and the Pacific plantains (the Iholena and Maoli-Popo'ulu subgroups).
[src:banana/banana-p01] Genetic evidence show that East African Highland bananas (AAA) originated from banana populations introduced to Africa from the region between Java, Borneo, and New Guinea.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Pacific plantains (AAB), on the other hand, were introduced to the Pacific Islands from banana populations originating from either eastern New Guinea or the Bismarck Archipelago.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Another wave of introductions later spread domesticated polyploid bananas to other parts of tropical Asia, particularly Indochina and the Indian subcontinent.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Southeast Asia remains the region of primary diversity of the banana.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Areas of secondary diversity are found in Africa, indicating a long history of banana cultivation there.
[src:banana/banana-p01] 21st century discoveries of alleged banana phytoliths in Uganda and Cameroon dating to the first millennium BC and earlier triggered a debate about the date of the first introduction of bananas to East Africa.
[src:banana/banana-p01] However, the identification of the remains in Uganda as phytoliths, much less banana phytoliths, is now considered dubious.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The Cameroon phytoliths, on the other hand, are confirmed as *Musa*, despite early doubts that they may be from *Ensete*.
[src:banana/banana-p01] An introduction date of 2000 to 1000 BC is also unlikely as this was long before there were any evidence of agriculture in East Africa.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Polyploid banana cultivars are sterile and do not spread without human cultivation.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Similarly, phytoliths recovered from the Kot Diji archaeological site in Pakistan were interpreted as evidence that bananas were known to the Indus Valley civilisation.
[src:banana/banana-p01] This may indicate very early dispersal of bananas by Austronesian traders by sea from as early as 2000 BCE.
[src:banana/banana-p01] But this is still putative, as they may have come from local wild *Musa* species used for fiber or as ornamentals, not food; and banana phytoliths are absent in other contemporary sites in South Asia.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Glucanase and two other proteins specific to Musaceae were found in dental calculus from the early Iron Age (12th century BCE) Philistines in Tel Erani in the southern Levant.
[src:banana/banana-p01] However, the authors only tentatively identify it as *Musa*, as the proteins can also be found in *Ensete* (cultivated for their edible corms and pseudostems in Africa).
[src:banana/banana-p01] The banana may have been present in isolated locations in the Middle East on the eve of Islam.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The spread of Islam was followed by far-reaching diffusion.
[src:banana/banana-p01] There are numerous references to it in Islamic texts (such as poems and hadiths) from the 9th century onwards.
[src:banana/banana-p01] By the 10th century, the banana appeared in texts from Palestine and Egypt.
[src:banana/banana-p01] From there, it diffused into North Africa and Al-Andalus (Islamic Spain) during the Arab Agricultural Revolution.
[src:banana/banana-p01] An article on banana tree cultivation is included in Ibn al-'Awwam's 12th-century agricultural work, *Kitāb al-Filāḥa* (*Book on Agriculture*).
[src:banana/banana-p01] During the Middle Ages, bananas from Granada were considered among the best in the Arab world.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Bananas were certainly grown in the Christian Kingdom of Cyprus by the late medieval period.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Writing in 1458, the Italian traveller and writer Gabriele Capodilista wrote favourably of the extensive farm produce of the estates at Episkopi, near modern-day Limassol, including the area's banana plantations.
[src:banana/banana-p01] In the early modern period, bananas were encountered by European explorers during the Magellan expedition in 1521, in both Guam and the Philippines.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Lacking a name for the fruit, the ship's historian Antonio Pigafetta described them as "figs more than one palm long." Bananas were introduced to South America by Portuguese sailors who brought them from West Africa in the 16th century.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Southeast Asian banana cultivars, as well as abaca grown for fibers, were introduced to North and Central America by the Spanish from the Philippines, via the Manila galleons.
[src:banana/banana-p01] In the 15th and 16th centuries, Portuguese colonists started banana plantations in the Atlantic Islands, Brazil, and western Africa.
[src:banana/banana-p01] North Americans began consuming bananas on a small scale at very high prices shortly after the Civil War, though it was only in the 1880s that the food became more widespread.
[src:banana/banana-p01] As late as the Victorian Era, bananas were not widely known in Europe, although they were available.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The earliest modern plantations originated in Jamaica and the related Western Caribbean Zone, including most of Central America.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Plantation cultivation involved the combination of modern transportation networks of steamships and railroads with the development of refrigeration that allowed more time between harvesting and ripening.
[src:banana/banana-p01] North American shippers like Lorenzo Dow Baker and Andrew Preston, the founders of the Boston Fruit Company started this process in the 1870s, with the participation of railroad builders like Minor C.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Development led to the multi-national giant corporations like Chiquita and Dole.
[src:banana/banana-p01] These companies were monopolistic, vertically integrated (controlling growing, processing, shipping and marketing) and usually used political manipulation to build enclave economies (internally self-sufficient, virtually tax exempt, and export-oriented, contributing little to the host economy).
[src:banana/banana-p01] The vast majority of the world's bananas are cultivated for family consumption or for sale on local markets.
[src:banana/banana-p01] They are grown in large quantities in India, while many other Asian and African countries host numerous small-scale banana growers who sell at least some of their crop.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Peasants with smallholdings of 1 to 2 acres in the Caribbean produce bananas for the world market, often alongside other crops.
[src:banana/banana-p01] In many tropical countries, the main cultivars produce green (unripe) bananas used for cooking.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Because bananas and plantains produce fruit year-round, they provide a valuable food source during the *hunger season* between harvests of other crops, and are thus important for global food security.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Bananas are propagated asexually from offshoots.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The plant is allowed to produce two shoots at a time; a larger one for immediate fruiting and a smaller "sucker" or "follower" to produce fruit in 6–8 months.
[src:banana/banana-p01] As a non-seasonal crop, bananas are available fresh year-round.
[src:banana/banana-p01] In global commerce in 2009, by far the most important cultivars belonged to the triploid *Musa acuminata* AAA group of Cavendish group bananas.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Disease is threatening the production of the Cavendish banana worldwide.
[src:banana/banana-p01] It is unclear if any existing cultivar can replace Cavendish bananas, so various hybridisation and genetic engineering programs are attempting to create a disease-resistant, mass-market banana.
[src:banana/banana-p01] One such strain that has emerged is the Taiwanese Cavendish or Formosana.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Export bananas are picked green, and ripened in special rooms upon arrival in the destination country.
[src:banana/banana-p01] These rooms are air-tight and filled with ethylene gas to induce ripening, which mimics the normal production of this gas as a ripening hormone.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Ethylene stimulates the formation of amylase, an enzyme that breaks down starch into sugar, influencing the taste.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Ethylene signals the production of pectinase, a different enzyme which breaks down the pectin between the cells of the banana, causing the banana to soften as it ripens.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The vivid yellow color many consumers in temperate climates associate with bananas is caused by ripening around 18 °C (64 °F), and does not occur in Cavendish bananas ripened in tropical temperatures (over 27 °C (81 °F)), which leaves them green.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Bananas are transported over long distances from the tropics to world markets.
[src:banana/banana-p01] To obtain maximum shelf life, harvest comes before the fruit is mature.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The fruit requires careful handling, rapid transport to ports, cooling, and refrigerated shipping.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The goal is to prevent the bananas from producing their natural ripening agent, ethylene.
[src:banana/banana-p01] This technology allows storage and transport for 3–4 weeks at 13 °C (55 °F).
[src:banana/banana-p01] On arrival, bananas are held at about 17 °C (63 °F) and treated with a low concentration of ethylene.
[src:banana/banana-p01] After a few days, the fruit begins to ripen and is distributed for final sale.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Ripe bananas can be held for a few days at home.
[src:banana/banana-p01] If bananas are too green, they can be put in a brown paper bag with an apple or tomato overnight to speed up the ripening process.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The excessive use of fertilizers contributes greatly to eutrophication in streams and lakes, harming aquatic life, while expanding banana production has led to deforestation.
[src:banana/banana-p01] As soil nutrients are depleted, more forest is cleared for plantations.
[src:banana/banana-p01] This causes soil erosion and increases the frequency of flooding.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Voluntary sustainability standards such as Rainforest Alliance and Fairtrade are being used to address some of these issues.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Banana production certified in this way grew rapidly at the start of the 21st century to represent 36% of banana exports by 2016.
[src:banana/banana-p01] However, such standards are applied mainly in countries which focus on the export market, such as Colombia, Costa Rica, Ecuador, and Guatemala; worldwide they cover only 8–10% of production.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Edible bananas are parthenocarpic (seedless).
[src:banana/banana-p01] This is important for their edibility, but the lack of seed production makes breeding difficult.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Furthermore, cultivated bananas are typically triploid (less commonly diploid, and a few tetraploid).
[src:banana/banana-p01] They are typically derived from the wild diploid species *M. acuminata* and *M. balbisiana*, although some originate from *M. acuminata* only.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Starting in the 1920s, "pedigree breeding" has been employed to try to generate desirable hybrids.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Existing triploids are bred against diploids, sometimes wild with a desired characteristic, trying to create a tetraploid by combining a haploid gamete from the diploid parent with a (rare) unreduced triploid gamete from the other.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The resulting tetraploid can then be bred against another diploid to produce triploid offspring.
[src:banana/banana-p01] More recently, the "reproductive breeding" strategy treats diploids with colchicine to produce tetraploid offspring, which can then be bred against a second diploid to produce triploids.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Mutation breeding can be used in this crop.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Aneuploidy is a source of significant variation in allotriploid varieties.
[src:banana/banana-p01] For one example, it can be a source of TR4 resistance.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Lab protocols have been devised to screen for such aberrations and for possible resulting disease resistances.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Wild *Musa* spp. provide useful resistance genetics, and are vital to breeding for TR4 resistance, as shown in introgressed resistance from wild relatives.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The Honduran Foundation for Agricultural Research has bred a seedless banana that is resistant to both Panama disease and black Sigatoka disease.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The team made use of the fact that "seedless" varieties do rarely produce seeds; they obtained around 15 seeds from some 30,000 cultivated plants, pollinated by hand with pollen from wild Asian bananas.
[src:banana/banana-p01] As of 2018, bananas are exported in larger volume and to a larger value than any other fruit.
[src:banana/banana-p01] In 2022, world production of bananas and plantains combined was 179 million tonnes, led by India and China with a combined total of 26% of global production.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Other major producers were Uganda, Indonesia, the Philippines, Nigeria and Ecuador.
[src:banana/banana-p01] As reported for 2013, total world exports were 20 million tonnes of bananas and 859,000 tonnes of plantains.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Ecuador and the Philippines were the leading exporters with 5.4 and 3.3 million tonnes, respectively, and the Dominican Republic was the leading exporter of plantains with 210,350 tonnes.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Banana production is affected by climate change through temperature, water stress, geography, light exposure, pests and disease, and carbon dioxide.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Overall, climate change from 1961 to 2016 suggests that climate change has had a net benefit on banana yields due to rising temperatures, but that these benefits are tapering off due to increased water demand and the challenge of growing companion crops like coffee.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Some major producing countries, notably India and China, are considered 'adaptable' as while they do show potential negative effects of climate change on yields, strong technology-yield trends may mitigate climate-driven yield declines.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Shifting bioclimatic zones in some areas, such as Nepal, mean that banana cultivation may increase in some areas as other crops, such as coffee, suffer the effects of climate change in the same region.
[src:banana/banana-p01] One study indicated the amount of area suited to banana growing in Nepal will grow by 40% by 2050, with some case studies showing benefit from the agroforestry technique of coffee-banana intercropping.
[src:banana/banana-p01] As part of these adaptations, "market opportunities for smallholder farmers need to be properly addressed through cooperatives or other such local bodies which secure adequate prices for farmers" (p.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Some banana diseases have spread in area due to climate change – for example, Black Sigatoka has spread from Honduras to Brazil, the Caribbean, and most recently, Florida.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Banana growing in Latin America and the Caribbean are predicted to have an increased risk of infection due to increased spore germination and growth, and wetter crop canopies.
[src:banana/banana-p01] However, predictions for Brazil suggest that due to reduced humidity, areas favorable to Black Sigatoka may decrease.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Bananas are negatively affected by flooding brought on or made worse by climate change.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Even in areas where drying reduces disease risk, the investment in needed irrigation systems could pressure freshwater resources and thus, "the impact of future climate change on banana production from the perspective of management must consider both the disease and the host" (p.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Also, farmers are limited by resources in drought management activities such as weeding, mulching, irrigation costs, and extra labor (p.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Bananas are damaged by a variety of pests, especially nematodes and insects.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Banana roots are subject to damage from multiple species of parasitic nematodes.
[src:banana/banana-p01] *Radopholus similis* causes nematode root rot, the most serious nematode disease of bananas in economic terms.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Root-knot is the result of infection by species of *Meloidogyne*, while root-lesion is caused by species of *Pratylenchus*, and spiral nematode root damage is the result of infection by *Helicotylenchus* species.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Among the main insect pests of banana cultivation are two beetles that cause substantial economic losses, the banana borer *Cosmopolites sordidus* and the banana stem weevil *Odoiporus longicollis*.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Other significant pests include aphids and scarring beetles.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Although in no danger of outright extinction, bananas of the Cavendish group, which dominate the global market, are under threat.
[src:banana/banana-p01] There is a need to enrich banana biodiversity by producing diverse new banana varieties, not just focusing on the Cavendish.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Its predecessor 'Gros Michel', discovered in the 1820s, was similarly dominant but had to be replaced after widespread infections of Panama disease.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Monocropping of Cavendish similarly leaves it susceptible to disease and so threatens both commercial cultivation and small-scale subsistence farming.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Within the data gathered from the genes of hundreds of bananas, the botanist Julie Sardos has found several wild banana ancestors currently unknown to scientists, whose genes could provide a means of defense against banana crop diseases.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Overall, fungal diseases are disproportionately important to small island developing states.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Prior to 1960, almost all commercial banana production centered on the Gros Michel cultivar, which was highly susceptible.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Cavendish was chosen as the replacement for Gros Michel because, among resistant cultivars, it produces the highest quality fruit.
[src:banana/banana-p01] It requires more care during shipping, and its quality compared to Gros Michel is debated.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Fusarium wilt TR4, a reinvigorated strain of Panama disease, was discovered in 1993.
[src:banana/banana-p01] This virulent form of Fusarium wilt has destroyed Cavendish plantations in several southeast Asian countries and spread to Australia and India.
[src:banana/banana-p01] As the soil-based fungi can easily be carried on boots, clothing, or tools, the wilt spread to the Americas despite years of preventive efforts.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Without genetic diversity, Cavendish is highly susceptible to TR4, and the disease endangers its commercial production worldwide.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The only known defense to TR4 is genetic resistance.
[src:banana/banana-p01] This is conferred either by RGA2, a gene isolated from a TR4-resistant diploid banana, or by the nematode-derived Ced9.
[src:banana/banana-p01] This may be achieved by genetic modification.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Black sigatoka is a fungal leaf spot disease first observed in Fiji in 1963 or 1964.
[src:banana/banana-p01] It is caused by the ascomycete *Mycosphaerella fijiensis*.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The disease, also called black leaf streak, has spread to banana plantations throughout the tropics from infected banana leaves used as packing material.
[src:banana/banana-p01] It affects all main cultivars of bananas and plantains (including the Cavendish cultivars), impeding photosynthesis by blackening parts of the leaves, eventually killing the entire leaf.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Starved for energy, fruit production falls by 50% or more, and the bananas that do grow ripen prematurely, making them unsuitable for export.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The fungus has shown ever-increasing resistance to treatment; spraying with fungicides may be required as often as 50 times a year.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Better strategies, with integrated pest management, are needed.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Banana bunchy top virus is a plant virus of the genus *Babuvirus*, family *Nanonviridae* affecting *Musa* spp.
[src:banana/banana-p01] (including banana, abaca, plantain and ornamental bananas) and *Ensete* spp. in the family *Musaceae*.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Banana bunchy top disease symptoms include dark green streaks of variable length in leaf veins, midribs and petioles.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Leaves become short and stunted as the disease progresses, becoming 'bunched' at the apex of the plant.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Infected plants may produce no fruit or the fruit bunch may not emerge from the pseudostem.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The virus is transmitted by the banana aphid *Pentalonia nigronervosa* and is widespread in Southeast Asia, Asia, the Philippines, Taiwan, Oceania and parts of Africa.
[src:banana/banana-p01] There is no cure, but it can be effectively controlled by the eradication of diseased plants and the use of virus-free planting material.
[src:banana/banana-p01] No resistant cultivars have been found, but varietal differences in susceptibility have been reported.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The commercially important Cavendish subgroup is severely affected.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Banana bacterial wilt is a bacterial disease caused by *Xanthomonas campestris* pv.
[src:banana/banana-p01] First identified on a close relative of bananas, *Ensete ventricosum*, in Ethiopia in the 1960s, The disease was first seen in Uganda in 2001 affecting all banana cultivars.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Since then it has been diagnosed in Central and East Africa, including the banana growing regions of Rwanda, the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Tanzania, Kenya, Burundi, and Uganda.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Given the narrow range of genetic diversity present in bananas and the many threats via biotic (pests and diseases) and abiotic threats (such as drought) stress, conservation of the full spectrum of banana genetic resources is ongoing.
[src:banana/banana-p01] In 2024, the economist Pascal Liu of the FAO described the impact of global warming as an "enormous threat" to the world supply of bananas.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Banana germplasm is conserved in many national and regional gene banks, and at the world's largest banana collection, the International *Musa* Germplasm Transit Centre, managed by Bioversity International and hosted at KU Leuven in Belgium.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Since *Musa* cultivars are mostly seedless, they are conserved by three main methods: *in vivo* (planted in field collections), *in vitro* (as plantlets in test tubes within a controlled environment), and by cryopreservation (meristems conserved in liquid nitrogen at −196 °C).
[src:banana/banana-p01] Genes from wild banana species are conserved as DNA and as cryopreserved pollen.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Seeds from wild species are sometimes conserved, although less commonly, as they are difficult to regenerate.
[src:banana/banana-p01] In addition, bananas and their crop wild relatives are conserved *in situ*, in the wild natural habitats where they evolved and continue to do so.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Diversity is also conserved in farmers' fields where continuous cultivation, adaptation and improvement of cultivars is often carried out by small-scale farmers growing traditional local cultivars.
[src:banana/banana-p01] A raw banana (not including the peel) is 75% water, 23% carbohydrates, 1% protein, and contains negligible fat.
[src:banana/banana-p01] A reference amount of 100 grams (3.5 oz) supplies 89 calories, 24% of the Daily Value of vitamin B6, and moderate amounts of vitamin C, manganese, potassium, and dietary fiber, with no other micronutrients in significant content (table).
[src:banana/banana-p01] Although bananas are commonly thought to contain exceptional potassium content, their actual potassium content is not high per typical food serving, having only 12% of the Daily Value for potassium (table).
[src:banana/banana-p01] The potassium-content ranking for bananas among fruits, vegetables, legumes, and many other foods is medium.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Bananas are a staple starch for many tropical populations.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Depending upon cultivar and ripeness, the flesh can vary in taste from starchy to sweet, and texture from firm to mushy.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Both the skin and inner part can be eaten raw or cooked.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The primary component of the aroma of fresh bananas is isoamyl acetate (also known as *banana oil*), which, along with several other compounds such as butyl acetate and isobutyl acetate, is a significant contributor to banana flavor.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Plantains are eaten cooked, often as fritters.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Pisang goreng, bananas fried with batter, is a popular street food in Southeast Asia.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Bananas feature in Philippine cuisine, with desserts like *maruya* banana fritters.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Bananas can be made into fruit preserves.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Banana chips are a snack produced from sliced and fried bananas, such as in Kerala.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Dried bananas are ground to make banana flour.
[src:banana/banana-p01] In Africa, matoke bananas are cooked in a sauce with meat and vegetables such as peanuts or beans to make the breakfast dish katogo.
[src:banana/banana-p01] In Western countries, bananas are used to make desserts such as banana bread.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Banana flowers (also called "banana hearts" or "banana blossoms") are used as a vegetable in South Asian and Southeast Asian cuisine.
[src:banana/banana-p01] As with artichokes, both the fleshy part of the bracts and the heart are edible.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Banana leaves are large, flexible, and waterproof.
[src:banana/banana-p01] While generally too tough to actually be eaten, they are often used as ecologically friendly disposable food containers or as "plates" in South Asia and several Southeast Asian countries.
[src:banana/banana-p01] In Indonesian cuisine, banana leaf is employed in cooking methods like pepes and botok; banana leaf packages containing food ingredients and spices are cooked in steam or in boiled water, or are grilled on charcoal.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Certain types of tamales are wrapped in banana leaves instead of corn husks.
[src:banana/banana-p01] In Malaysia, banana leaves are traditionally used as a food wrap for nasi lemak.
[src:banana/banana-p01] While banana leaves are not an essential ingredient, it imparts a subtle, vegetal aroma that enhances the flavor of the dish.
[src:banana/banana-p01] When banana leaves are used for steaming or grilling, they protect the food ingredients from burning and add a subtle sweet flavor.
[src:banana/banana-p01] In South India, it is customary to serve traditional food on a banana leaf.
[src:banana/banana-p01] In Tamil Nadu (India), dried banana leaves are used as to pack food and to make cups to hold liquid food items.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The tender core of the banana plant's trunk is also used in South Asian and Southeast Asian cuisine.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Examples include the Burmese dish *mohinga*, and the Filipino dishes *inubaran* and *kadyos, manok, kag ubad*.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Fiber harvested from the pseudostems and leaves of the abacá banana (*Musa textilis*) and other bananas have been used for textiles in the Philippines since ancient times.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Archaeological evidence of cloth-weaving tools like spindle whorls date back to the period between 1000 BC and 500 AD in the Philippines.
[src:banana/banana-p01] However, the tropical environment and the sparsity of pre-colonial records makes it hard to trace its antiquity.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Nevertheless, abacá bananas are the main source of fibers for traditional textiles still woven among various ethnic groups of the Philippines.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Examples of abacá-based textiles include the *t'nalak*, made by the Tiboli tribe of South Cotabato, and *dagmay*, made by the Bagobo people.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Traditional abacá cloth collected from the Philippines during the Spanish colonial period is found in museum collections around the world, like the Boston Museum of Fine Arts and the Textile Museum of Canada.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The oldest surviving example of textile made from banana fibers is the Banton Burial Cloth recovered from a coffin in the sacred Ipot Cave of Banton, Romblon, Philippines, and dated to around the 13th and 14th centuries.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Aside from indigenous clothing for native Filipinos, *medriñaque* was also used during the colonial era as canvas for sails and for stiffening clothing like skirts, collars, and doublets.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The inner fibers are also used in the making of hats, including the "Manila hats", hammocks, matting, cordage, ropes, coarse twines, and Manila paper.
[src:banana/banana-p01] By the 19th century, abacá fiber had become one of the most important economic exports of the Philippines.
[src:banana/banana-p01] They were in demand due to their strength and saltwater-resistance.
[src:banana/banana-p01] A similar tradition of weaving banana textiles (from *Musa basjoo* and *Musa balbisiana*) also existed among the non-Han minority groups in southern China since at least the Han Dynasty (202 BC – 220 BC).
[src:banana/banana-p01] Both fruit-bearing and fibrous banana species have been used.
[src:banana/banana-p01] This textile tradition along with the banana species *Musa basjoo* (Japanese *bashō*, 芭蕉) was introduced to the Ryukyu Islands of Japan at around the 14th century.
[src:banana/banana-p01] In the Japanese system of kijōka-bashōfu, leaves and shoots are cut from the plant periodically to ensure softness.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Harvested shoots are first boiled in lye to prepare fibers for yarn-making.
[src:banana/banana-p01] These banana shoots produce fibers of varying degrees of softness, yielding yarns and textiles with differing qualities for specific uses.
[src:banana/banana-p01] For example, the outermost fibers of the shoots are the coarsest, and are suitable for tablecloths, while the softest innermost fibers are desirable for kimono and kamishimo.
[src:banana/banana-p01] This traditional Japanese cloth-making process requires many steps, all performed by hand.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Banana paper can be made either from the bark of the banana plant, mainly for artistic purposes, or from the fibers of the stem and non-usable fruits.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The paper may be hand-made or industrially processed.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The large leaves of bananas are locally used as umbrellas.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Banana peel may have capability to extract heavy metal contamination from river water, similar to other purification materials.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Waste bananas can be used to feed livestock.
[src:banana/banana-p01] As with all living things, potassium-containing bananas emit radioactivity at low levels occurring naturally from the potassium-40 (K-40) isotope.
[src:banana/banana-p01] The banana equivalent dose of radiation was developed in 1995 as a simple teaching-tool to educate the public about the natural, small amount of K-40 radiation occurring in everyone and in common foods.
[src:banana/banana-p01] Individuals with a latex allergy may experience a reaction to handling or eating bananas.
[src:banana/banana-p02] The Edo period poet Matsuo Bashō is named after the Japanese word 芭蕉 (*Bashō*) for the Japanese banana.
[src:banana/banana-p02] The *Bashō* planted in his garden by a grateful student became a source of inspiration to his poetry, as well as a symbol of his life and home.
[src:banana/banana-p02] We Have No Bananas" was written by Frank Silver and Irving Cohn and originally released in 1923; for many decades, it was the best-selling sheet music in history.
[src:banana/banana-p02] Since then the song has been rerecorded several times and has been particularly popular during banana shortages.
[src:banana/banana-p02] A person slipping on a banana peel has been a staple of physical comedy for generations.
[src:banana/banana-p02] An American comedy recording from 1910 features a popular character of the time, "Uncle Josh", claiming to describe his own such incident.
[src:banana/banana-p02] The banana's suggestively phallic shape has been exploited in artworks from Giorgio de Chirico's 1913 painting *The Uncertainty of the Poet* onwards.
[src:banana/banana-p02] In 2019, an exhibition of Natalia LL's video and set of photographs showing a woman "sucking on a banana" at the National Museum in Warsaw was taken down and the museum's director reprimanded.
[src:banana/banana-p02] The cover artwork for the 1967 debut album of The Velvet Underground features a banana made by Andy Warhol.
[src:banana/banana-p02] On the original vinyl LP version, the design allowed the listener to "peel" this banana to find a pink, peeled banana on the inside.
[src:banana/banana-p02] In 1989, the feminist Guerilla Girls made a screenprint with two bananas, intentionally reminiscent of Warhol's, arranged to form a "0" to answer the question in the artwork, "How many works by women artists were in the Andy Warhol and Tremaine auctions at Sotheby's?".
[src:banana/banana-p02] Italian artist Maurizio Cattelan created a 2019 concept art piece titled *Comedian* involving taping a banana to a wall using silver duct tape.
[src:banana/banana-p02] The piece was exhibited briefly at the Art Basel in Miami before being removed from the exhibition and eaten without permission in another artistic stunt titled *Hungry Artist* by New York artist David Datuna.
[src:banana/banana-p02] In India, bananas serve a prominent part in many festivals and occasions of Hindus.
[src:banana/banana-p02] In South Indian weddings, particularly Tamil weddings, banana trees are tied in pairs to form an arch as a blessing to the couple for a long-lasting, useful life.
[src:banana/banana-p02] In Thailand, it is believed that a certain type of banana plant may be inhabited by a spirit, Nang Tani, a type of ghost related to trees and similar plants that manifests itself as a young woman.
[src:banana/banana-p02] People often tie a length of colored satin cloth around the pseudostem of the banana plants.
[src:banana/banana-p02] In Malay folklore, the ghost known as Pontianak is associated with banana plants (*pokok pisang*), and its spirit is said to reside in them during the day.
[src:banana/banana-p02] In European, British, and Australian sport, throwing a banana at a member of an opposing team has long been used as a form of racial abuse.
[src:banana/banana-p02] The act, which was commonplace in England in the 1980s, is meant to taunt players of Black African ancestry by equating them to apes or monkeys.
